{"title_page": "1936 Catalan coup d'\u00e9tat attempt", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Attempted Catalan coup of 1936\n|partof=[[Interwar period]]\n|image=\u041a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0446\u043e\u0432 \u041d\u0430 \u0421\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443 \u0411\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0435\u043b\u043e\u043d\u0430 9\u0430\u0432\u043317 1936.JPG\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=[[Barcelona]], late 1936\n|place=[[Catalonia]]\n|date=November 1936\n|result=coup prevented\n|combatant1=* {{nowrap|{{Flagicon image|Flag of Catalonia.svg}} [[Generalitat de Catalunya|Generalitat]]}}\n* {{flagicon image|Bandera CNT-FAI.svg}} [[Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional del Trabajo|CNT]]-[[Federaci\u00f3n Anarquista Ib\u00e9rica|FAI]]\n|combatant2=* {{nowrap|{{Flagicon image|Estelada blava.svg}} [[Estat Catal\u00e0]]}}\n|commander1=[[Llu\u00eds Companys]]<br /> [[:ca:Josep Tarradellas i Joan|Josep Tarradellas]]<br /> [[:ca:Dion\u00eds Eroles i Batlle|Dionisio Eroles]]<br /> [[:ca:Artemi Aiguader i Mir\u00f3|Artemio Aiguader]]<br /> [[:ca:Aurelio Fern\u00e1ndez S\u00e1nchez|Aurelio Fern\u00e1ndez]]<br /> Joans Solans\n|commander2=[[:ca:Josep Maria Xammar i Sala|Josep Mar\u00eda Xammar]]<br /> [[:ca:Joan Casanovas i Maristany|Joan Casanovas]]<br /> [[:ca:Andreu Revert\u00e9s|Andreu Revert\u00e9s]]<br />  Manuel Blasi<br />  [[:ca:Joan Torres i Picart|Joan Torres-Picart]]<br /> [[:ca:Joan Cornudella i Barber\u00e0|Joan Cornudella]]\n|strength1=Generalitat troops, CNT militia\n|strength2=EC militia and other formations\n|casualties3=\n|}}\n'''Catalan coup d\u2019etat (1936)''' was a violent takeover of power in [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia of 1932|autonomous]] [[Catalonia]], planned by the [[Catalan nationalism|independentist]] party [[Estat Catal\u00e0]]. The conspirators intended to declare total independence of Catalonia as a state neutral in the [[Spanish Civil War]], and to marginalize all non-aligned political groupings, especially the [[Anarchism in Spain|Anarchists]]. They counted on party militias and Catalan army and security units, infiltrated by the Estat Catal\u00e0 militants. The coup was planned in November, as the plotters assumed that the central [[Republican faction (Spanish Civil War)|Republican]] government, absorbed by the [[battle of Madrid]], would not be able to take action. The plot failed because of the Anarchist counter-action, who exposed the scheme and some of its leaders. In pre-emptive strike [[Generalitat]] services detained a few of the conspirators; the others fled to [[Third French Republic|France]]. Estat Catal\u00e0 was sidelined, while [[Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional del Trabajo|CNT]]-[[Federaci\u00f3n Anarquista Ib\u00e9rica|FAI]] ensured its dominant position in Catalonia. The attempted coup remains a poorly researched and rather unknown episode; in [[historiography]] it is discussed against the background of Catalan [[fascism]].\n==Background==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-11543, Madrid, Ausrufung der Zweiten Spanischen Republik.jpg|thumb|left|[[Second Spanish Republic|Republic]] declared, Barcelona 1931]]\nSince the late 19th century along traditional political groupings \u2013 [[Conservative Party (Spain)|Conservatives]], [[Liberalism in Spain|Liberals]], [[Carlists]], [[Republicanism in Spain|Republicans]] \u2013 there were new currents emerging in Catalonia: [[PSOE|Socialists]], [[Communist Party of Spain|Communists]], Anarchists and [[Catalan nationalism|Catalan Nationalists]]. The last two of these were getting increasingly popular. Their social basis partially overlapped, though the Anarchists catered mostly to urban [[proletariat]], while the Catalanists gained dynamics among the mid-lower strata. While competing in terms of popular mobilization, they nevertheless pursued the same anti-system and left-wing course.<ref> detailed analysis of social radicalization in Catalonia in Stanley G. Payne, ''The Spanish Revolution'', Madison 1970, ISBN 97803930988853, see esp. the chapter ''The Social Struggle in Barcelon''a, pp. 37-61</ref> Following the fall of the monarchy in 1931 various currents of Catalanism converged in [[Esquerra Republicana de Catalunya]] (ERC), the centre-left federative party structure which dominated the [[Parliament of Catalonia|autonomous Catalan parliament]]. The Anarchists, who by default boycotted any electoral action, focused rather on expansion of their nationwide trade union, Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional de Trabajo (CNT). Their structures actively engaged against the state and in late 1933 managed to mount insurgent action which [[:es:Insurrecci\u00f3n anarquista de diciembre de 1933|rocked most of Catalonia]].<ref>discussion of the Anarchists and their position versus other left-wing groupings in Payne 1970, pp. 112-130</ref>\n\nIn October 1934 parts of Northern Spain were engulfed by [[Asturian miners' strike of 1934|revolutionary turmoil]]; the Catalanists took advantage of the chaos and [[Events of 6 October|declared the independence of Catalonia]]. The Anarchists did nothing to support their cause; instead, their labored to introduce own [[Anarcho-syndicalism|anarcho-syndicalist]] communes. The ERC-controlled autonomous government Generalitat cracked down on anarchist structures;<ref>some scholars believe that in October 1934 the Generalitat president, representative of mainstream ERC Lluis Companys was manipulated by radical nationalists of Estat Catal\u00e0, chiefly by Josep Denc\u00e0s and Miquel Badia, see Abel Paz, ''Durruti in the Spanish Revolution'', Edinburgh 2007, ISBN 9781904859505, p. 339</ref> following outbursts of violence mutual aversion between the two was already bordering hostility.<ref> Payne 1970, pp. 150-152</ref> During the [[Spanish general election, 1936|general elections of February 1936]] the Anarchists hesitantly decided to support the [[Popular Front (Spain)|Popular Front]] alliance, which included ERC, but soon truce gave way to tension. In April the Anarchist hit-squad murdered [[Miquel Badia]], who in 1934 engineered and executed the repressive anti-CNT campaign. The Catalanists themselves got increasingly divided over policy towards the central government and the radical Left. Many lambasted Generalitat for appeasement and demanded a more decisive stand. In May 1936 Estat Catal\u00e0 (EC), a group which so far formed part of ERC, left the federation.<ref>Antonio Gasc\u00f3n Ricao, ''El complot de Estat Catal\u00e0 contra Companys'', [in:] Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157, pp. 90-92</ref>\n\n==Estat Catal\u00e0==\n[[File:Nosaltres sols 3.png|thumb|160px|''Nosaltres Sols!'' bulletin]]\nEstat Catal\u00e0 was a Catalan nationalist organization which emerged in the early 1920s, distinct from other Catalanist groupings due to its extreme anti-establishment position and left-wing social outlook. Since the early 1930s EC was getting increasingly radical and adopted a militant stand; its uniformed paramilitary [[militia]], the [[:ca:Escamots d'Estat Catal\u00e0|Escamots]], were outlawed following a series of violent episodes. In the mid-1930s EC entered ERC and formed its radical, left wing. Having left Esquerra in May 1936 the party regained its fully independent status and became the key vehicle of revolutionary Catalan nationalism.<ref> Daniel D\u00edaz Esculies, ''Estat Catal\u00e0 contra Companys'', [in:] Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157, pp. 77-79</ref> It was soon merged with two other, smaller and equally radical parties of Catalanist left: [[Nosaltres Sols!]]<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 92-93</ref> and [[Catalan Nationalist Party|Partit Nacionalista Catal\u00e0]].<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 94</ref> The command layer of the united organization was formed by the EC leader [[:ca:Josep Denc\u00e0s i Puigdollers|Josep Dencas]], the former NS! chief, an ideologue Manuel Blasi, and the former president of PNC [[:ca:Josep Maria Xammar i Sala|Josep Maria Xammar]]. The integration process was still ongoing when in July 1936 Spain was rocked by the [[Spanish coup of July 1936|military coup d\u2019etat]].<ref>in the early summer of 1936 Estat Catal\u00e0 numbered some 6,000 members, Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 92</ref>\n\nMany EC members actively resisted the [[Nationalist faction (Spanish Civil War)|military rebels]]; during the fightings they seized large quantities of arms. In the already revolutionary ambience the party moved to new headquarters in the Oro de Rhin restaurant by the [[Gran Via (Barcelona)|Gran V\u00eda]], launched a new daily bulletin ''Diari de Barcelona'' and commenced massive recruitment to its militia ranks.<ref> some of the already formed EC militia units were dispatched to fight the Nationalists, either on the Aragon front or taking part in invasion of the Balearic Islands, Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 94</ref> Representatives of EC joined numerous inter-party bodies competing for power, especially [[:es:Comit\u00e8 Central de Mil\u00edcies Antifeixistes de Catalunya|Comit\u00e8 de Mil\u00edcies Antifeixistes]]; however, the party did not enter the coalition Generalitat government.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 94-95</ref> Relations with the Anarchists, who in aftermath of the failed military coup emerged as the dominant political grouping in Catalonia, remained tense. In August the CNT commando tried to plunder the main EC office and their representatives in the government demanded that Dencas, along the murdered Badia blamed for anti-Anarchist violence of 1934, be detained. By September he fled the country, fearing for his life.<ref>when it turned out that when on exile, Dencas settled in Fascist Italy, EC expulsed him from the party ranks</ref> The party jefatura was assumed by its former secretary, [[:ca:Joan Torres i Picart|Joan Torres-Picart]].<ref> Torres-Picart was acceptable to all 3 factions forming the party: the historical Estat Catal\u00e1, Nosaltres Sols! and PNC, Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, ''La ley de silencio: el \u201ecomplot nacionalista\u201d contra Companys, noviembre-diciembre de 1936'', [in:] Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157, p. 131</ref>\n\n==Jockeying for position==\n[[File:Strijdlustige vrouw - Woman ready to fight (3334194838).jpg|thumb|left|revolution in Barcelona, 1936]]\nIn the summer of 1936 Generalitat decided to form a Catalan army, the [[People's Army of Catalonia]]. Supported by most parties \u2013 though not by the Anarchists \u2013 the government started to form first units.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 93-94</ref> Estat Catal\u00e0 remained very active in the process; its people dominated 3 battalions to be deployed along the French border and known as Mil\u00edcies Pirinenques (MP). Their officer corps was very much composed of militants related earlier to OMNS, Organizaci\u00f3 Militar Nosaltres Sols, a cadre military section of Nosaltres Sols!.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 94</ref> During the fall first MP sub-units indeed started to take over control points on the [[Pyrenees|Pyrenean]] border with France; not in few locations skirmishes with local Anarchist units, so far manning the posts, ensued.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, s.</ref> The own EC party initiative was raising a large, 700-men battalion [[:es:Columna Volant Catalana|Columna Volant Catalana]]; it was originally to be sent to the [[Aragon]] front, but did not enter into action; its sub-units were stationed across various locations of the [[Lerida (province)|Lerida province]].<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 95-96</ref> Other party militia units were being reorganized by the former Escamots commander, [[:ca:Joan Cornudella i Barber\u00e0|Joan Cornudella]]. \n\nSince the late summer of 1936 the EC party press was getting increasingly explicit about the need to \"Catalanize\" the ongoing revolution; decreasingly enigmatic articles suggested that the process was about getting Catalan independence declared and about having all non-aligned political groupings, principally the Anarchists, marginalized.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 96</ref> Xammar talked to [[Llu\u00eds Companys|president Companys]] about breaking the Anarchist domination in the region. He also demanded that EC people get nominated to high positions in the Generalitat security; Companys did not seem interested.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 96-96</ref> The second-in-command person in the autonomous Catalan structures, the prime minister and the parliament speaker [[:ca:Joan Casanovas i Maristany|Joan Casanovas]], was more tractable; the EC member in the 1920s, later he remained in the ERC mainstream. He started to voice publicly about the need to reinforce the state and assume responsibility for bold action,<ref> Josep Mar\u00eda Pascual, ''Un complot desconocido'', [in:] Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157, p. 67</ref> which was broadly taken for a hardly veiled criticism of vacillating Generalitat policy.<ref>a historian claims that while Companys intended to play the Anarchists versus the Communists, Casanovas opted for a less subtle forceful solution, Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 96-97</ref> These declarations triggered open conflict between Companys and Casanovas; in September the latter was dismissed from premiership. His seat was taken by a close Companys associate, [[Josep Tarradellas]].<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 96</ref>\n\n==Gear-up to action==\n[[File:La-Esquella-de-la-Torratxa-1936.jpg|thumb|160px|Catalan nationalist-revolutionary propaganda]]\nHistorians assume that since early October 1936 the EC leaders started to discuss a violent takeover of power in autonomous Catalonia, possibly by means of a [[coup d\u2019etat]]. Their key asset were armed units controlled by the party, including the militia, the forces of Columna Volant and the MP battalions; some were supposed to enter into action in Barcelona, and some were expected to seize power in other cities and towns of the region.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 97</ref> The conspiracy network was being developed within local administrative or revolutionary institutions.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 97</ref> Xammar negotiated with acquiescent officials in various committees in Northern Catalonia about a would-be joint action against the Anarchists.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 96-97</ref> The conspirators assumed that the Generalitat security would at least remain passive; since early October the Commissar of Public Order, the de facto police chief in Catalonia,<ref> Francisco J. Romero Salvad\u00f3, ''Historical Dictionary of the Spanish Civil War'', London 2013, ISBN 9780810857841, p. 123</ref> was a former EC militant [[:ca:Andreu Revert\u00e9s|Andreu Revert\u00e9s]]. Thought the Anarchists protested his nomination, it was enforced by Companys, the decision related to some private links between the two.<ref> Companys\u2019 second wife, Carmen Ballester, was good friend to Revertes\u2019 partner. Herself she was once the wife of EC militant Carles Duran, and since 1933 the lover of another EC activist, Miguel Badia, Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 105. Some historians claim that in the Republic days Revertes was routinely procuring women for top Estat Catala politicians, Luis P\u00edo Moa Rodriguez, ''Los nacionalismos vasco y catal\u00e1n: En la Guerra Civil, el franquismo y la democracia'', Madrid 2013, ISBN 9788490552421, p. 57</ref>\n\nThe EC envoys [[:ca:Josep Maria Batista i Roca|Josep Maria Batista i Roca]] and Nicolau Rubi\u00f3 i Serralach sounded the French and British diplomats in Spain about would-be recognition of independent Catalonia; outcome of these conversations is not clear.<ref> D\u00edaz Esculies 2012, p. 81</ref> Most likely the same issue was discussed with [[Mussolini]] envoys.<ref> details are not known. EC men, and especially Josep Dencas, were talking to Mussolini or his representatives on recognition of independent Catalonia already during the Republic era, Payne 1970, p. 286</ref> Another Estat Catal\u00e0 delegate Vicen\u00e7 Borrell travelled to [[Brussels]] to speak to [[Francesc Camb\u00f3]], the historic leader of right-wing Catalanists. However, Camb\u00f3 did not seem interested; at the time he was anticipating a swift triumph of the [[Nationalist faction (Spanish Civil War)|Nationalists]].<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 98</ref> Since early November EC scaled up their radical, national-socialist propaganda campaign. During numerous rallies Borrell, Cornudella, Xammar, and Torres-Picart vehemently criticised irresolute Generalitat policy. To much surprise, one of their meetings hosted Casanovas; in belligerent tone he declared that the time for bold action was near and spoke with contempt about the Catalan parliament, the body he still presided. Casanovas received numerous adhesion messages, including many from various EC militia units.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 98-99</ref>\n\n==Climax==\n[[File:Woman with cntfai flag-3-.jpg|thumb|160px|left|[[Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional del Trabajo|CNT]] triumphant]]\nIn early November the Nationalist troops were advancing at the outskirts of [[Madrid]] and it might have appeared that the fall of the Republic was imminent. In mid-November CV and MP units stationed in various locations in Catalonia were put on alert.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 99</ref> Though a strong EC militia formation, known as Columna Hermanos Badia, was sent to the Madrid front, a so-called 2. Batali\u00f3n Mil\u00edcies Pirinenques got gathered in the Barcelona barracks.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 100</ref> A transport of arms and munitions entered the country from France; it was organized by Revertes, who ensured that the Generalitat money is used to finance the delivery, though none of high government officials was aware of it.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 101</ref> The train was directed at a depot station on the Barcelona suburbs;<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 101</ref> distribution of hundreds of rifles and grenades among specific EC-controlled units was discussed at a meeting of November 22, attended by Revert\u00e9s, Casanovas, Torres-Picart, Xammar and Cornudella.<ref> D\u00edaz Esculies 2012, p. 82. It is not clear who was the moving spirit behind the scheme. Some scholars point to Xammar, \"hombre fuerte\" of EC</ref> Detachments commanded by EC men were to seize the [[Palau de la Generalitat de Catalunya|Generalitat buildings]] and detain all government members; in case of resistance, they were to be shot.<ref> according to other authors, the EC insurgents intended to shot members of Comite de Milicias Antifascistas, Pascual 2012, p. 68</ref> Companys \u2013 also to be shot if intransigent \u2013 was to be replaced as president by Casanovas.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 104</ref> Some scholars suspect that Revert\u00e9s planned to seize the transport of [[Bank of Spain]] gold, on transit from [[Cartagena, Spain|Cartagena]] to France, but the theory is rejected by other historians.<ref> referred after Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Huertas Claveria, Antonio Ribas, ''El complot que queria catalanizar en 1936 la revoluci\u00f3n popular'', [in:] Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157, p. 70</ref>\n\nOn November 24 the Generalitat services detained Revert\u00e9s; one theory is that the action was an own initiative of his inferior, jefe of Servicios de Orden P\u00fablico [[:ca:Dion\u00eds Eroles i Batlle|Dionisio Eroles]], another one is that Eroles obtained authorization of Tarradellas or other high government officials beforehand.<ref> Huertas Claveria, Ribas 2012, p. 69</ref> Eroles, himself a CNT member in structures of the security department, developed his own network of Anarchist informers. He apparently monitored Revert\u00e9s\u2019 activity and decided to act once he realized the coup was near.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 103; another theory is that Revert\u00e9s used security forces to settle his private business and this is how he got uncovered, Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 103</ref> Revert\u00e9s, immediately dismissed from his job, was for a few hours interrogated by Eroles, his secretary Joan Solans and secretary of the Internal Security Council [[:ca:Aurelio Fern\u00e1ndez S\u00e1nchez|Aurelio Fern\u00e1ndez]]. Initially they suggested he commits suicide; Revert\u00e9s apparently refused.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 103</ref> It seems that eventually there was sort of a deal closed; Revert\u00e9s agreed to denounce his accomplices, while in return he was to be allowed to leave Spain.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 104</ref> The Interior Minister [[:ca:Artemi Aiguader i Mir\u00f3|Artemio Aiguader]] directed a wave of arrests which ensued.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 104</ref> Torres-Picart ended up behind bars;<ref> according to others Torres-Picart was detained even earlier than Revert\u00e9s, Francisco Bonamusa, ''Tensiones en el consejo ejecutivo de la Generalitat'', [in:] Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157, p. 88</ref> as Casanovas enjoyed the [[parliamentary immunity]], he found himself under police surveillance.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 107</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Funeral of Leonese anarquist Buenaventura Durruti in Barcelona, there was Llu\u00eds Companys and Joan Garc\u00eda Oliver.jpg|thumb|[[Companys]] and the Anarchist leader [[Garcia Oliver]]]]\nGeneralitat administration did not decide to mount a massive repressive action; only some 100 people were arrested.<ref> Payne 1970, p. 286</ref> Some Anarchist groups intended to set up a makeshift tribunal and bring before it those charged with crime against state, but in unclear circumstances the plan was abandoned; the CNT militia ransacked ''Diari de Barcelona'' offices and the EC headquarters.<ref> Huertas Claveria, Ribas 2012, p. 70</ref> Official press very vaguely informed about dismissal of Revert\u00e9s,<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 102</ref> and Aiguader\u2019s public comments remained enigmatic to the extreme.<ref> see ''La Vanguardia'' 26.11.1936, available [http://hemeroteca.lavanguardia.com/preview/1936/11/25/pagina-1/33141879/pdf.html here]</ref> The [[Mundo Obrero|Catalan Anarchist press]] launched a massive onslaught against Estat Catal\u00e0.<ref> it was directed by the national Anarchist mouthpiece, the Barcelona-based Solidaridad Obrera, D\u00edaz Esculies 2012, p. 84</ref> EC has not been outlawed; while Torres-Picart remained in custody, Cornudella declared himself the party leader; it soon condemned and expulsed all members deemed involved. The role of Cornudella is not clear; some scholars suspect he might have acted in accord with Eroles.<ref> Huertas Claveria, Ribas 2012, p. 71</ref> The EC-controlled militia, paramilitary and army units were dispatched to the front, where they later fought valiantly and loyally.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 110</ref> \n\nRevert\u00e9s spent the next few days jailed in the [[Montju\u00efc|Montju\u00efc prison]], and was later murdered in highly unclear circumstances. According to one theory he was shot in Barcelona shortly after he had left prison,<ref> it is claimed that when Revert\u00e9s was declared released he refused to leave the cell fearing for his life; Aiguader personally ensured him of safety. In line with the old tradition of killing inmates by faking their escape, he was allegedly shot few meters from the prison walls, Huertas Claveria, Ribas 2012, p. 71</ref> according to another members of the personal Companys guard shot him on November 30 in [[Calaf]], already on his way to [[Andorra]].<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 105. One more version is that he was executed following a kangaroo trial, which condemned Revert\u00e9s to death for alleged financial misdemeanor, Payne 1970, p. 286</ref> Casanovas as a high state official was quietly allowed to leave the country,<ref> Payne 1970, p. 286</ref> while investigation launched by Tribunal de Casac\u00edon was eventually closed with no charges advanced.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 106</ref> Torres-Picart in picturesque and also unclear circumstances managed to leave prison and made it to France; from there he launched a vehement campaign against Companys.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 108</ref> Xammar with his family crossed the Spanish-French frontier before any action was taken against him;<ref> D\u00edaz Esculies 2012, p. 83</ref> France was also the target of few high Generalitat officials, like Josep Maria Espanya.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 108</ref> Manuel Blasi, at the time commanding an EC militia unit in Aragon, was detained by the Anarchists there; following a few weeks he was released and by the end of 1936 he also left Spain.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 108</ref>\n\n==Epilogue==\n[[File:FrancoenReus.jpg|thumb|left|[[Francoism]] in Catalonia]]\nCasanovas returned to Catalonia after [[May Days of Barcelona|May 1937]], when the Anarchist domination in Catalonia had been broken, and \u2013 still as the parliament speaker \u2013 tried to arrange a separatist Catalan declaration of neutrality; he died in 1942 in France.<ref> Jes\u00fas Mestre i Campi (ed.), ''Diccionari d'hist\u00f2ria de Catalunya'', Barcelona 2004, ISBN 9788441218857, p. 207</ref> Espanya, Xammar and Torres-Picart left France for [[Latin America]], where they lived until the end of their days; Espanya died in 1953, Xammar in 1967,<ref> Vicen\u00e7 Riera i Llorca, ''Els exiliats catalans a M\u00e8xic'', Barcelona 1994, ISBN 9788472569720, p. 33</ref> and Torres-Picart in 1988; before death he managed to visit the already [[Spanish transition to democracy|democratic Spain]]. Cornudella and Blasi after 1939 returned to Spain and engaged in anti-[[Francoism|Francoist]] conspiracy, both repressed; the former was elected to the Catalan parliament after 1975 and passed away in 1985,<ref> see Ferm\u00ed Rubiralta i Casas, ''Joan Cornudella i Barber\u00e0 (1904-1985): biografia pol\u00edtica: 50 anys d'independentisme catal\u00e0'', Montserrat 2003, ISBN 9788484155195</ref> it is not clear when the latter died. Remnants of \u00e9migr\u00e9 Estat Catal\u00e1 structures languished for decades until the party was registered in Spain in 1977; now it is a rather marginal grouping, even though the Catalan nationalism [[Catalan independence referendum, 2017|is at its heyday]].\n\nFollowing the [[Fall of Catalonia|fall of Catalonia]] Companys left to France; handed over to the Francoists in 1940, he was executed the same year. Tarradellas lived in France and America and was a longtime president of the Geerralitat of the \u00e9migr\u00e9 Catalan government; having returned to Spain in 1977 he was one of the best-known Catalan politicians until his death in 1988. Eroles, Aiguader and Fern\u00e1ndez were dismissed from Generalitat security structures following the 1937 Barcelona May Days. In 1939 Eroles left to France and in unclear circumstances, possibly murdered, perished in 1940.<ref> Secundino Serrano, ''La \u00faltima gesta: los republicanos que vencieron a Hitler (1939-1945)'', Madrid 2005, ISBN 9788403096066, p. 90</ref> The other two left France for [[Mexico]]; Aiguader died there in 1946,<ref> Josep M. Poblet, ''Jaume Aiguader: Una vida \"amb Catalunya i per Catalunya\"'', Barcelona 1977, ISBN 843078327X</ref> Fern\u00e1ndez passed away in 1971.<ref> Agust\u00edn Guillam\u00f3n, ''Biograf\u00eda de del luchador anarquista Aurelio Fern\u00e1ndez S\u00e1nchez (1897-1971)'', [in:] ''Kaosenlared'' service 10.05.2018, available [https://kaosenlared.net/biografia-de-del-luchador-anarquista-aurelio-fernandez-sanchez-1897-1971/ here]</ref> The fate of Solans is unknown. The Catalan anarchism deteriorated during Francoism and after 1975 was reborn as a minoritarian political force; today CNT is a small syndicalist organization. Of all protagonists of the November 1936 events, only Companys and Tarradellas are currently remembered and honored in the Catalan public space.\n\n==Propaganda and historiography==\n[[File:Open books stacked.jpg|thumb]]\nAs except the Anarchists none of the parties involved banked on the November 1936 episode propagandawise, it soon went into oblivion; in public memory it was almost totally eclipsed by the May 1937 struggle for power in the Republican Barcelona. Also after the war the EC conspiracy was largely ignored by all parties. From the Francoist perspective it was somewhat inconvenient as incompatible with vision of a homogenous, criminal red horde. None one of the post-Republican \u00e9migr\u00e9 groupings saw sufficient propaganda potential of the episode. For historians it remained a rather difficult chapter of Spanish past. The Generalitat archives documented the repressive action rather than the plot itself; most EC papers have gone missing, while memoirs and other accounts provided by the protagonists were trapped in conflicting versions, inconsistencies, and political bias.<ref> Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157</ref>\n\nFirst serious attempts to target the issue come from the 1980s;<ref> Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Huertas Claveria, Antonio Ribas, ''El complot que queria catalanizar en 1936 la revoluci\u00f3n popular'', [in:] ''El Periodico'' 25.11.1984, pp. 17-18; Daniel Diaz i Esculies, ''Objectiu: Matar Companys'', [in:] ''Avenc'' 225 (1988), pp. 7-12</ref> historiography for decades to come did not pay much attention, referred the question in passim<ref>see e.g. very superficial \u2013 though not erroneous - remarks in classical work on the Spanish Civil War by Hugh Thomas, who adhered to the \u201eReverter\u201d, spelling, repeated also by Payne and Romero Salgado</ref> and at times suggested erroneous interpretations.<ref> e.g. as late as in 2008 two historians claimed, that Revertes let the success go to his head; he allegedly indulged in countless and chaotic detention orders, triggering a counter-action against him, Victor Alba, Stephen Schwartz, ''Spanish Marxism Versus Soviet Communism: A History of the P.O.U.M. in the Spanish Civil War'', London 2008, ISBN 9781412834940, p. 188</ref> A multi-angle joint analysis of the issue was published in 2012, but many of the authors remain extremely cautious, adhere to hypothetical narrative and suggest that their conclusions should be approached as preliminary.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 91-110</ref> Most scholars participating agree that there was a nationalist conspiracy unfolding, though it is not clear whether it was a few EC politicians or rather the party structures engaged. It is neither known how much the plans of the coup were advanced and whether the decision to rise was in fact taken.<ref>some historians do not dwell upon a plot or a coup d\u2019etat, but focus rather on separatist negotiations about neutrality of Catalonia; counter-action of CNT is hence presented as an attempt to compromise EC, see e.g. Payne 1970, p. 286</ref> Historians are not sure whether counter-action was triggered by CNT, Generalitat or other political groups. Many detailed questions remain unanswered, e.g. the one about the role of Casanovas.<ref> Ucelay-Da Cal 2012, pp. 130-131</ref> The Catalan coup of 1936 is discussed against the background of some broader issues, like this of the Catalan fascism.<ref> see Arnau Gonz\u00e0lez i Vilalta, Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Xos\u00e9 Manoel N\u00fa\u00f1ez Seixas, ''El catalanisme davant del feixisme (1919-2018)'', Barcelona 2018, ISBN 9788417082734, Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, ''Los \u201emalos de la pel\u00edcula\u201d: las Joventuts d\u2019Esquerra Republicana \u2013 Estat Catal\u00e1 y la problem\u00e1tica de un \u201efascismo catal\u00e1n\u201d'', [in:] ''Ayer'' 59 (2005), pp. 147-172</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* Arnau Gonz\u00e0lez i Vilalta, Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Xos\u00e9 Manoel N\u00fa\u00f1ez Seixas, ''El catalanisme davant del feixisme (1919-2018)'', Barcelona 2018, ISBN 9788417082734\n* Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, ''\u201cEl complot nacionalista\u201d contra Companys. Novembre-desembre del 1936'', [in:] J. M. Sol\u00e9 i Sabat\u00e9 (ed.), ''La Guerra Civil a Catalunya'', vol. 3, Barcelona 2004, ISBN 9788429754162, ss. 205-214\n* Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157\n* Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, ''Estat Catala: The Strategies of Separation and Revolution of Catalan Radical Nationalism'' [PhD thesis Columbia Univeristy], New York 1974\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6FPsTaiZn_w the coup as mentioned in TV series (1986) on the civil war, 19:50 to 21:00]\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1936]]\n[[Category:1930s coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts]]\n[[Category:20th century in Catalonia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Attempted Catalan coup of 1936\n|partof=[[Interwar period]]\n|image=\u041a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0446\u043e\u0432 \u041d\u0430 \u0421\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443 \u0411\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0435\u043b\u043e\u043d\u0430 9\u0430\u0432\u043317 1936.JPG\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=[[Barcelona]], late 1936\n|place=[[Catalonia]]\n|date=November 1936\n|result=coup prevented\n|combatant1=* {{nowrap|{{Flagicon image|Flag of Catalonia.svg}} [[Generalitat de Catalunya|Generalitat]]}}\n* {{flagicon image|Bandera CNT-FAI.svg}} [[Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional del Trabajo|CNT]]-[[Federaci\u00f3n Anarquista Ib\u00e9rica|FAI]]\n|combatant2=* {{nowrap|{{Flagicon image|Estelada blava.svg}} [[Estat Catal\u00e0]]}}\n|commander1=[[Llu\u00eds Companys]]<br /> [[:ca:Josep Tarradellas i Joan|Josep Tarradellas]]<br /> [[:ca:Dion\u00eds Eroles i Batlle|Dionisio Eroles]]<br /> [[:ca:Artemi Aiguader i Mir\u00f3|Artemio Aiguader]]<br /> [[:ca:Aurelio Fern\u00e1ndez S\u00e1nchez|Aurelio Fern\u00e1ndez]]<br /> Joans Solans\n|commander2=[[:ca:Josep Maria Xammar i Sala|Josep Mar\u00eda Xammar]]<br /> [[:ca:Joan Casanovas i Maristany|Joan Casanovas]]<br /> [[:ca:Andreu Revert\u00e9s|Andreu Revert\u00e9s]]<br />  Manuel Blasi<br />  [[:ca:Joan Torres i Picart|Joan Torres-Picart]]<br /> [[:ca:Joan Cornudella i Barber\u00e0|Joan Cornudella]]\n|strength1=Generalitat troops, CNT militia\n|strength2=EC militia and other formations\n|casualties3=\n|}}\n'''Catalan coup d\u2019etat (1936)''' was a violent takeover of power in [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia of 1932|autonomous]] [[Catalonia]], planned by the [[Catalan nationalism|independentist]] party [[Estat Catal\u00e0]]. The conspirators intended to declare total independence of Catalonia as a state neutral in the [[Spanish Civil War]], and to marginalize all non-aligned political groupings, especially the [[Anarchism in Spain|Anarchists]]. They counted on party militias and Catalan army and security units, infiltrated by the Estat Catal\u00e0 militants. The coup was planned in November, as the plotters assumed that the central [[Republican faction (Spanish Civil War)|Republican]] government, absorbed by the [[battle of Madrid]], would not be able to take action. The plot failed because of the Anarchist counter-action, who exposed the scheme and some of its leaders. In pre-emptive strike [[Generalitat]] services detained a few of the conspirators; the others fled to [[Third French Republic|France]]. Estat Catal\u00e0 was sidelined, while [[Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional del Trabajo|CNT]]-[[Federaci\u00f3n Anarquista Ib\u00e9rica|FAI]] ensured its dominant position in Catalonia. The attempted coup remains a poorly researched and rather unknown episode; in [[historiography]] it is discussed against the background of Catalan [[fascism]].\n==Background==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-11543, Madrid, Ausrufung der Zweiten Spanischen Republik.jpg|thumb|left|[[Second Spanish Republic|Republic]] declared, Barcelona 1931]]\nSince the late 19th century along traditional political groupings \u2013 [[Conservative Party (Spain)|Conservatives]], [[Liberalism in Spain|Liberals]], [[Carlists]], [[Republicanism in Spain|Republicans]] \u2013 there were new currents emerging in Catalonia: [[PSOE|Socialists]], [[Communist Party of Spain|Communists]], Anarchists and [[Catalan nationalism|Catalan Nationalists]]. The last two of these were getting increasingly popular. Their social basis partially overlapped, though the Anarchists catered mostly to urban [[proletariat]], while the Catalanists gained dynamics among the mid-lower strata. While competing in terms of popular mobilization, they nevertheless pursued the same anti-system and left-wing course.<ref> detailed analysis of social radicalization in Catalonia in Stanley G. Payne, ''The Spanish Revolution'', Madison 1970, ISBN 97803930988853, see esp. the chapter ''The Social Struggle in Barcelon''a, pp. 37-61</ref> Following the fall of the monarchy in 1931 various currents of Catalanism converged in [[Esquerra Republicana de Catalunya]] (ERC), the centre-left federative party structure which dominated the [[Parliament of Catalonia|autonomous Catalan parliament]]. The Anarchists, who by default boycotted any electoral action, focused rather on expansion of their nationwide trade union, Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional de Trabajo (CNT). Their structures actively engaged against the state and in late 1933 managed to mount insurgent action which [[:es:Insurrecci\u00f3n anarquista de diciembre de 1933|rocked most of Catalonia]].<ref>discussion of the Anarchists and their position versus other left-wing groupings in Payne 1970, pp. 112-130</ref>\n\nIn October 1934 parts of Northern Spain were engulfed by [[Asturian miners' strike of 1934|revolutionary turmoil]]; the Catalanists took advantage of the chaos and [[Events of 6 October|declared the independence of Catalonia]]. The Anarchists did nothing to support their cause; instead, their labored to introduce own [[Anarcho-syndicalism|anarcho-syndicalist]] communes. The ERC-controlled autonomous government Generalitat cracked down on anarchist structures;<ref>some scholars believe that in October 1934 the Generalitat president, representative of mainstream ERC Lluis Companys was manipulated by radical nationalists of Estat Catal\u00e0, chiefly by Josep Denc\u00e0s and Miquel Badia, see Abel Paz, ''Durruti in the Spanish Revolution'', Edinburgh 2007, ISBN 9781904859505, p. 339</ref> following outbursts of violence mutual aversion between the two was already bordering hostility.<ref> Payne 1970, pp. 150-152</ref> During the [[Spanish general election, 1936|general elections of February 1936]] the Anarchists hesitantly decided to support the [[Popular Front (Spain)|Popular Front]] alliance, which included ERC, but soon truce gave way to tension. In April the Anarchist hit-squad murdered [[Miquel Badia]], who in 1934 engineered and executed the repressive anti-CNT campaign. The Catalanists themselves got increasingly divided over policy towards the central government and the radical Left. Many lambasted Generalitat for appeasement and demanded a more decisive stand. In May 1936 Estat Catal\u00e0 (EC), a group which so far formed part of ERC, left the federation.<ref>Antonio Gasc\u00f3n Ricao, ''El complot de Estat Catal\u00e0 contra Companys'', [in:] Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157, pp. 90-92</ref>\n\n==Estat Catal\u00e0==\n[[File:Nosaltres sols 3.png|thumb|160px|''Nosaltres Sols!'' bulletin]]\nEstat Catal\u00e0 was a Catalan nationalist organization which emerged in the early 1920s, distinct from other Catalanist groupings due to its extreme anti-establishment position and left-wing social outlook. Since the early 1930s EC was getting increasingly radical and adopted a militant stand; its uniformed paramilitary [[militia]], the [[:ca:Escamots d'Estat Catal\u00e0|Escamots]], were outlawed following a series of violent episodes. In the mid-1930s EC entered ERC and formed its radical, left wing. Having left Esquerra in May 1936 the party regained its fully independent status and became the key vehicle of revolutionary Catalan nationalism.<ref> Daniel D\u00edaz Esculies, ''Estat Catal\u00e0 contra Companys'', [in:] Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157, pp. 77-79</ref> It was soon merged with two other, smaller and equally radical parties of Catalanist left: [[Nosaltres Sols!]]<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 92-93</ref> and [[Catalan Nationalist Party|Partit Nacionalista Catal\u00e0]].<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 94</ref> The command layer of the united organization was formed by the EC leader [[:ca:Josep Denc\u00e0s i Puigdollers|Josep Dencas]], the former NS! chief, an ideologue Manuel Blasi, and the former president of PNC [[:ca:Josep Maria Xammar i Sala|Josep Maria Xammar]]. The integration process was still ongoing when in July 1936 Spain was rocked by the [[Spanish coup of July 1936|military coup d\u2019etat]].<ref>in the early summer of 1936 Estat Catal\u00e0 numbered some 6,000 members, Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 92</ref>\n\nMany EC members actively resisted the [[Nationalist faction (Spanish Civil War)|military rebels]]; during the fightings they seized large quantities of arms. In the already revolutionary ambience the party moved to new headquarters in the Oro de Rhin restaurant by the [[Gran Via (Barcelona)|Gran V\u00eda]], launched a new daily bulletin ''Diari de Barcelona'' and commenced massive recruitment to its militia ranks.<ref> some of the already formed EC militia units were dispatched to fight the Nationalists, either on the Aragon front or taking part in invasion of the Balearic Islands, Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 94</ref> Representatives of EC joined numerous inter-party bodies competing for power, especially [[:es:Comit\u00e8 Central de Mil\u00edcies Antifeixistes de Catalunya|Comit\u00e8 de Mil\u00edcies Antifeixistes]]; however, the party did not enter the coalition Generalitat government.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 94-95</ref> Relations with the Anarchists, who in aftermath of the failed military coup emerged as the dominant political grouping in Catalonia, remained tense. In August the CNT commando tried to plunder the main EC office and their representatives in the government demanded that Dencas, along the murdered Badia blamed for anti-Anarchist violence of 1934, be detained. By September he fled the country, fearing for his life.<ref>when it turned out that when on exile, Dencas settled in Fascist Italy, EC expulsed him from the party ranks</ref> The party jefatura was assumed by its former secretary, [[:ca:Joan Torres i Picart|Joan Torres-Picart]].<ref> Torres-Picart was acceptable to all 3 factions forming the party: the historical Estat Catal\u00e1, Nosaltres Sols! and PNC, Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, ''La ley de silencio: el \u201ecomplot nacionalista\u201d contra Companys, noviembre-diciembre de 1936'', [in:] Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157, p. 131</ref>\n\n==Jockeying for position==\n[[File:Strijdlustige vrouw - Woman ready to fight (3334194838).jpg|thumb|left|revolution in Barcelona, 1936]]\nIn the summer of 1936 Generalitat decided to form a Catalan army, the [[People's Army of Catalonia]]. Supported by most parties \u2013 though not by the Anarchists \u2013 the government started to form first units.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 93-94</ref> Estat Catal\u00e0 remained very active in the process; its people dominated 3 battalions to be deployed along the French border and known as Mil\u00edcies Pirinenques (MP). Their officer corps was very much composed of militants related earlier to OMNS, Organizaci\u00f3 Militar Nosaltres Sols, a cadre military section of Nosaltres Sols!.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 94</ref> During the fall first MP sub-units indeed started to take over control points on the [[Pyrenees|Pyrenean]] border with France; not in few locations skirmishes with local Anarchist units, so far manning the posts, ensued.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, s.</ref> The own EC party initiative was raising a large, 700-men battalion [[:es:Columna Volant Catalana|Columna Volant Catalana]]; it was originally to be sent to the [[Aragon]] front, but did not enter into action; its sub-units were stationed across various locations of the [[Lerida (province)|Lerida province]].<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 95-96</ref> Other party militia units were being reorganized by the former Escamots commander, [[:ca:Joan Cornudella i Barber\u00e0|Joan Cornudella]]. \n\nSince the late summer of 1936 the EC party press was getting increasingly explicit about the need to \"Catalanize\" the ongoing revolution; decreasingly enigmatic articles suggested that the process was about getting Catalan independence declared and about having all non-aligned political groupings, principally the Anarchists, marginalized.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 96</ref> Xammar talked to [[Llu\u00eds Companys|president Companys]] about breaking the Anarchist domination in the region. He also demanded that EC people get nominated to high positions in the Generalitat security; Companys did not seem interested.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 96-96</ref> The second-in-command person in the autonomous Catalan structures, the prime minister and the parliament speaker [[:ca:Joan Casanovas i Maristany|Joan Casanovas]], was more tractable; the EC member in the 1920s, later he remained in the ERC mainstream. He started to voice publicly about the need to reinforce the state and assume responsibility for bold action,<ref> Josep Mar\u00eda Pascual, ''Un complot desconocido'', [in:] Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157, p. 67</ref> which was broadly taken for a hardly veiled criticism of vacillating Generalitat policy.<ref>a historian claims that while Companys intended to play the Anarchists versus the Communists, Casanovas opted for a less subtle forceful solution, Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 96-97</ref> These declarations triggered open conflict between Companys and Casanovas; in September the latter was dismissed from premiership. His seat was taken by a close Companys associate, [[Josep Tarradellas]].<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 96</ref>\n\n==Gear-up to action==\n[[File:La-Esquella-de-la-Torratxa-1936.jpg|thumb|160px|Catalan nationalist-revolutionary propaganda]]\nHistorians assume that since early October 1936 the EC leaders started to discuss a violent takeover of power in autonomous Catalonia, possibly by means of a [[coup d\u2019etat]]. Their key asset were armed units controlled by the party, including the militia, the forces of Columna Volant and the MP battalions; some were supposed to enter into action in Barcelona, and some were expected to seize power in other cities and towns of the region.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 97</ref> The conspiracy network was being developed within local administrative or revolutionary institutions.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 97</ref> Xammar negotiated with acquiescent officials in various committees in Northern Catalonia about a would-be joint action against the Anarchists.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 96-97</ref> The conspirators assumed that the Generalitat security would at least remain passive; since early October the Commissar of Public Order, the de facto police chief in Catalonia,<ref> Francisco J. Romero Salvad\u00f3, ''Historical Dictionary of the Spanish Civil War'', London 2013, ISBN 9780810857841, p. 123</ref> was a former EC militant [[:ca:Andreu Revert\u00e9s|Andreu Revert\u00e9s]]. Thought the Anarchists protested his nomination, it was enforced by Companys, the decision related to some private links between the two.<ref> Companys\u2019 second wife, Carmen Ballester, was good friend to Revertes\u2019 partner. Herself she was once the wife of EC militant Carles Duran, and since 1933 the lover of another EC activist, Miguel Badia, Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 105. Some historians claim that in the Republic days Revertes was routinely procuring women for top Estat Catala politicians, Luis P\u00edo Moa Rodriguez, ''Los nacionalismos vasco y catal\u00e1n: En la Guerra Civil, el franquismo y la democracia'', Madrid 2013, ISBN 9788490552421, p. 57</ref>\n\nThe EC envoys [[:ca:Josep Maria Batista i Roca|Josep Maria Batista i Roca]] and Nicolau Rubi\u00f3 i Serralach sounded the French and British diplomats in Spain about would-be recognition of independent Catalonia; outcome of these conversations is not clear.<ref> D\u00edaz Esculies 2012, p. 81</ref> Most likely the same issue was discussed with [[Mussolini]] envoys.<ref> details are not known. EC men, and especially Josep Dencas, were talking to Mussolini or his representatives on recognition of independent Catalonia already during the Republic era, Payne 1970, p. 286</ref> Another Estat Catal\u00e0 delegate Vicen\u00e7 Borrell travelled to [[Brussels]] to speak to [[Francesc Camb\u00f3]], the historic leader of right-wing Catalanists. However, Camb\u00f3 did not seem interested; at the time he was anticipating a swift triumph of the [[Nationalist faction (Spanish Civil War)|Nationalists]].<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 98</ref> Since early November EC scaled up their radical, national-socialist propaganda campaign. During numerous rallies Borrell, Cornudella, Xammar, and Torres-Picart vehemently criticised irresolute Generalitat policy. To much surprise, one of their meetings hosted Casanovas; in belligerent tone he declared that the time for bold action was near and spoke with contempt about the Catalan parliament, the body he still presided. Casanovas received numerous adhesion messages, including many from various EC militia units.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 98-99</ref>\n\n==Climax==\n[[File:Woman with cntfai flag-3-.jpg|thumb|160px|left|[[Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional del Trabajo|CNT]] triumphant]]\nIn early November the Nationalist troops were advancing at the outskirts of [[Madrid]] and it might have appeared that the fall of the Republic was imminent. In mid-November CV and MP units stationed in various locations in Catalonia were put on alert.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 99</ref> Though a strong EC militia formation, known as Columna Hermanos Badia, was sent to the Madrid front, a so-called 2. Batali\u00f3n Mil\u00edcies Pirinenques got gathered in the Barcelona barracks.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 100</ref> A transport of arms and munitions entered the country from France; it was organized by Revertes, who ensured that the Generalitat money is used to finance the delivery, though none of high government officials was aware of it.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 101</ref> The train was directed at a depot station on the Barcelona suburbs;<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 101</ref> distribution of hundreds of rifles and grenades among specific EC-controlled units was discussed at a meeting of November 22, attended by Revert\u00e9s, Casanovas, Torres-Picart, Xammar and Cornudella.<ref> D\u00edaz Esculies 2012, p. 82. It is not clear who was the moving spirit behind the scheme. Some scholars point to Xammar, \"hombre fuerte\" of EC</ref> Detachments commanded by EC men were to seize the [[Palau de la Generalitat de Catalunya|Generalitat buildings]] and detain all government members; in case of resistance, they were to be shot.<ref> according to other authors, the EC insurgents intended to shot members of Comite de Milicias Antifascistas, Pascual 2012, p. 68</ref> Companys \u2013 also to be shot if intransigent \u2013 was to be replaced as president by Casanovas.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 104</ref> Some scholars suspect that Revert\u00e9s planned to seize the transport of [[Bank of Spain]] gold, on transit from [[Cartagena, Spain|Cartagena]] to France, but the theory is rejected by other historians.<ref> referred after Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Huertas Claveria, Antonio Ribas, ''El complot que queria catalanizar en 1936 la revoluci\u00f3n popular'', [in:] Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157, p. 70</ref>\n\nOn November 24 the Generalitat services detained Revert\u00e9s; one theory is that the action was an own initiative of his inferior, jefe of Servicios de Orden P\u00fablico [[:ca:Dion\u00eds Eroles i Batlle|Dionisio Eroles]], another one is that Eroles obtained authorization of Tarradellas or other high government officials beforehand.<ref> Huertas Claveria, Ribas 2012, p. 69</ref> Eroles, himself a CNT member in structures of the security department, developed his own network of Anarchist informers. He apparently monitored Revert\u00e9s\u2019 activity and decided to act once he realized the coup was near.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 103; another theory is that Revert\u00e9s used security forces to settle his private business and this is how he got uncovered, Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 103</ref> Revert\u00e9s, immediately dismissed from his job, was for a few hours interrogated by Eroles, his secretary Joan Solans and secretary of the Internal Security Council [[:ca:Aurelio Fern\u00e1ndez S\u00e1nchez|Aurelio Fern\u00e1ndez]]. Initially they suggested he commits suicide; Revert\u00e9s apparently refused.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 103</ref> It seems that eventually there was sort of a deal closed; Revert\u00e9s agreed to denounce his accomplices, while in return he was to be allowed to leave Spain.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 104</ref> The Interior Minister [[:ca:Artemi Aiguader i Mir\u00f3|Artemio Aiguader]] directed a wave of arrests which ensued.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 104</ref> Torres-Picart ended up behind bars;<ref> according to others Torres-Picart was detained even earlier than Revert\u00e9s, Francisco Bonamusa, ''Tensiones en el consejo ejecutivo de la Generalitat'', [in:] Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157, p. 88</ref> as Casanovas enjoyed the [[parliamentary immunity]], he found himself under police surveillance.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 107</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Funeral of Leonese anarquist Buenaventura Durruti in Barcelona, there was Llu\u00eds Companys and Joan Garc\u00eda Oliver.jpg|thumb|[[Companys]] and the Anarchist leader [[Garcia Oliver]]]]\nGeneralitat administration did not decide to mount a massive repressive action; only some 100 people were arrested.<ref> Payne 1970, p. 286</ref> Some Anarchist groups intended to set up a makeshift tribunal and bring before it those charged with crime against state, but in unclear circumstances the plan was abandoned; the CNT militia ransacked ''Diari de Barcelona'' offices and the EC headquarters.<ref> Huertas Claveria, Ribas 2012, p. 70</ref> Official press very vaguely informed about dismissal of Revert\u00e9s,<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 102</ref> and Aiguader\u2019s public comments remained enigmatic to the extreme.<ref> see ''La Vanguardia'' 26.11.1936, available [http://hemeroteca.lavanguardia.com/preview/1936/11/25/pagina-1/33141879/pdf.html here]</ref> The [[Mundo Obrero|Catalan Anarchist press]] launched a massive onslaught against Estat Catal\u00e0.<ref> it was directed by the national Anarchist mouthpiece, the Barcelona-based Solidaridad Obrera, D\u00edaz Esculies 2012, p. 84</ref> EC has not been outlawed; while Torres-Picart remained in custody, Cornudella declared himself the party leader; it soon condemned and expulsed all members deemed involved. The role of Cornudella is not clear; some scholars suspect he might have acted in accord with Eroles.<ref> Huertas Claveria, Ribas 2012, p. 71</ref> The EC-controlled militia, paramilitary and army units were dispatched to the front, where they later fought valiantly and loyally.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 110</ref> \n\nRevert\u00e9s spent the next few days jailed in the [[Montju\u00efc|Montju\u00efc prison]], and was later murdered in highly unclear circumstances. According to one theory he was shot in Barcelona shortly after he had left prison,<ref> it is claimed that when Revert\u00e9s was declared released he refused to leave the cell fearing for his life; Aiguader personally ensured him of safety. In line with the old tradition of killing inmates by faking their escape, he was allegedly shot few meters from the prison walls, Huertas Claveria, Ribas 2012, p. 71</ref> according to another members of the personal Companys guard shot him on November 30 in [[Calaf]], already on his way to [[Andorra]].<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 105. One more version is that he was executed following a kangaroo trial, which condemned Revert\u00e9s to death for alleged financial misdemeanor, Payne 1970, p. 286</ref> Casanovas as a high state official was quietly allowed to leave the country,<ref> Payne 1970, p. 286</ref> while investigation launched by Tribunal de Casac\u00edon was eventually closed with no charges advanced.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 106</ref> Torres-Picart in picturesque and also unclear circumstances managed to leave prison and made it to France; from there he launched a vehement campaign against Companys.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 108</ref> Xammar with his family crossed the Spanish-French frontier before any action was taken against him;<ref> D\u00edaz Esculies 2012, p. 83</ref> France was also the target of few high Generalitat officials, like Josep Maria Espanya.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 108</ref> Manuel Blasi, at the time commanding an EC militia unit in Aragon, was detained by the Anarchists there; following a few weeks he was released and by the end of 1936 he also left Spain.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, p. 108</ref>\n\n==Epilogue==\n[[File:FrancoenReus.jpg|thumb|left|[[Francoism]] in Catalonia]]\nCasanovas returned to Catalonia after [[May Days of Barcelona|May 1937]], when the Anarchist domination in Catalonia had been broken, and \u2013 still as the parliament speaker \u2013 tried to arrange a separatist Catalan declaration of neutrality; he died in 1942 in France.<ref> Jes\u00fas Mestre i Campi (ed.), ''Diccionari d'hist\u00f2ria de Catalunya'', Barcelona 2004, ISBN 9788441218857, p. 207</ref> Espanya, Xammar and Torres-Picart left France for [[Latin America]], where they lived until the end of their days; Espanya died in 1953, Xammar in 1967,<ref> Vicen\u00e7 Riera i Llorca, ''Els exiliats catalans a M\u00e8xic'', Barcelona 1994, ISBN 9788472569720, p. 33</ref> and Torres-Picart in 1988; before death he managed to visit the already [[Spanish transition to democracy|democratic Spain]]. Cornudella and Blasi after 1939 returned to Spain and engaged in anti-[[Francoism|Francoist]] conspiracy, both repressed; the former was elected to the Catalan parliament after 1975 and passed away in 1985,<ref> see Ferm\u00ed Rubiralta i Casas, ''Joan Cornudella i Barber\u00e0 (1904-1985): biografia pol\u00edtica: 50 anys d'independentisme catal\u00e0'', Montserrat 2003, ISBN 9788484155195</ref> it is not clear when the latter died. Remnants of \u00e9migr\u00e9 Estat Catal\u00e1 structures languished for decades until the party was registered in Spain in 1977; now it is a rather marginal grouping, even though the Catalan nationalism [[Catalan independence referendum, 2017|is at its heyday]].\n\nFollowing the [[Fall of Catalonia|fall of Catalonia]] Companys left to France; handed over to the Francoists in 1940, he was executed the same year. Tarradellas lived in France and America and was a longtime president of the Geerralitat of the \u00e9migr\u00e9 Catalan government; having returned to Spain in 1977 he was one of the best-known Catalan politicians until his death in 1988. Eroles, Aiguader and Fern\u00e1ndez were dismissed from Generalitat security structures following the 1937 Barcelona May Days. In 1939 Eroles left to France and in unclear circumstances, possibly murdered, perished in 1940.<ref> Secundino Serrano, ''La \u00faltima gesta: los republicanos que vencieron a Hitler (1939-1945)'', Madrid 2005, ISBN 9788403096066, p. 90</ref> The other two left France for [[Mexico]]; Aiguader died there in 1946,<ref> Josep M. Poblet, ''Jaume Aiguader: Una vida \"amb Catalunya i per Catalunya\"'', Barcelona 1977, ISBN 843078327X</ref> Fern\u00e1ndez passed away in 1971.<ref> Agust\u00edn Guillam\u00f3n, ''Biograf\u00eda de del luchador anarquista Aurelio Fern\u00e1ndez S\u00e1nchez (1897-1971)'', [in:] ''Kaosenlared'' service 10.05.2018, available [https://kaosenlared.net/biografia-de-del-luchador-anarquista-aurelio-fernandez-sanchez-1897-1971/ here]</ref> The fate of Solans is unknown. The Catalan anarchism deteriorated during Francoism and after 1975 was reborn as a minoritarian political force; today CNT is a small syndicalist organization. Of all protagonists of the November 1936 events, only Companys and Tarradellas are currently remembered and honored in the Catalan public space.\n\n==Propaganda and historiography==\n[[File:Open books stacked.jpg|thumb]]\nAs except the Anarchists none of the parties involved banked on the November 1936 episode propagandawise, it soon went into oblivion; in public memory it was almost totally eclipsed by the May 1937 struggle for power in the Republican Barcelona. Also after the war the EC conspiracy was largely ignored by all parties. From the Francoist perspective it was somewhat inconvenient as incompatible with vision of a homogenous, criminal red horde. None one of the post-Republican \u00e9migr\u00e9 groupings saw sufficient propaganda potential of the episode. For historians it remained a rather difficult chapter of Spanish past. The Generalitat archives documented the repressive action rather than the plot itself; most EC papers have gone missing, while memoirs and other accounts provided by the protagonists were trapped in conflicting versions, inconsistencies, and political bias.<ref> Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157</ref>\n\nFirst serious attempts to target the issue come from the 1980s;<ref> Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Huertas Claveria, Antonio Ribas, ''El complot que queria catalanizar en 1936 la revoluci\u00f3n popular'', [in:] ''El Periodico'' 25.11.1984, pp. 17-18; Daniel Diaz i Esculies, ''Objectiu: Matar Companys'', [in:] ''Avenc'' 225 (1988), pp. 7-12</ref> historiography for decades to come did not pay much attention, referred the question in passim<ref>see e.g. very superficial \u2013 though not erroneous - remarks in classical work on the Spanish Civil War by Hugh Thomas, who adhered to the \u201eReverter\u201d, spelling, repeated also by Payne and Romero Salgado</ref> and at times suggested erroneous interpretations.<ref> e.g. as late as in 2008 two historians claimed, that Revertes let the success go to his head; he allegedly indulged in countless and chaotic detention orders, triggering a counter-action against him, Victor Alba, Stephen Schwartz, ''Spanish Marxism Versus Soviet Communism: A History of the P.O.U.M. in the Spanish Civil War'', London 2008, ISBN 9781412834940, p. 188</ref> A multi-angle joint analysis of the issue was published in 2012, but many of the authors remain extremely cautious, adhere to hypothetical narrative and suggest that their conclusions should be approached as preliminary.<ref> Gasc\u00f3n Ricao 2012, pp. 91-110</ref> Most scholars participating agree that there was a nationalist conspiracy unfolding, though it is not clear whether it was a few EC politicians or rather the party structures engaged. It is neither known how much the plans of the coup were advanced and whether the decision to rise was in fact taken.<ref>some historians do not dwell upon a plot or a coup d\u2019etat, but focus rather on separatist negotiations about neutrality of Catalonia; counter-action of CNT is hence presented as an attempt to compromise EC, see e.g. Payne 1970, p. 286</ref> Historians are not sure whether counter-action was triggered by CNT, Generalitat or other political groups. Many detailed questions remain unanswered, e.g. the one about the role of Casanovas.<ref> Ucelay-Da Cal 2012, pp. 130-131</ref> The Catalan coup of 1936 is discussed against the background of some broader issues, like this of the Catalan fascism.<ref> see Arnau Gonz\u00e0lez i Vilalta, Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Xos\u00e9 Manoel N\u00fa\u00f1ez Seixas, ''El catalanisme davant del feixisme (1919-2018)'', Barcelona 2018, ISBN 9788417082734, Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, ''Los \u201emalos de la pel\u00edcula\u201d: las Joventuts d\u2019Esquerra Republicana \u2013 Estat Catal\u00e1 y la problem\u00e1tica de un \u201efascismo catal\u00e1n\u201d'', [in:] ''Ayer'' 59 (2005), pp. 147-172</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* Arnau Gonz\u00e0lez i Vilalta, Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Xos\u00e9 Manoel N\u00fa\u00f1ez Seixas, ''El catalanisme davant del feixisme (1919-2018)'', Barcelona 2018, ISBN 9788417082734\n* Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, ''\u201cEl complot nacionalista\u201d contra Companys. Novembre-desembre del 1936'', [in:] J. M. Sol\u00e9 i Sabat\u00e9 (ed.), ''La Guerra Civil a Catalunya'', vol. 3, Barcelona 2004, ISBN 9788429754162, ss. 205-214\n* Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, Arnau Gonz\u00e1lez i Vilalta (ed.), ''Contra Companys, 1936. La frustraci\u00f3n nacionalista ante la revoluci\u00f3n'', Valencia 2012, ISBN 9788437089157\n* Enric Ucelay-Da Cal, ''Estat Catala: The Strategies of Separation and Revolution of Catalan Radical Nationalism'' [PhD thesis Columbia Univeristy], New York 1974\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K0F3rMi3B7M hagiographic version of EC history on ''YouTube'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6FPsTaiZn_w the coup as mentioned in TV series (1986) on the civil war, 19:50 to 21:00]\n* [https://www.cnt.es/ official CNT website]\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1936]]\n[[Category:1930s coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts]]\n[[Category:20th century in Catalonia]]\n", "name_user": "Charicaric", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1936_Catalan_coup_d%27%C3%A9tat_attempt"}
{"title_page": "Rachaf", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Rachaf\n| native_name             =  \u0631\u0634\u0627\u0641\n| native_name_lang        = ara<!-- ISO 639-2 code: \"fr\" for French, \"ara\" for Arabic -->\n| settlement_type         = Village\n\n| image_skyline           =\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           =\n\n| pushpin_map             = Lebanon\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = Map showing the location of Rachaf within Lebanon\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location within Lebanon\n\n| coordinates             = {{coord|33|09|N|35|22|E|region:LB_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{flagcountry|Lebanon}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Governorates of Lebanon|Governorate]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Districts of Lebanon|District]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Nabatieh Governorate]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Bint Jbeil District]]\n\n| established_title       = <!-- Founded -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 =\n\n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             =\n\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 700\n| elevation_min_m         = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n\n| population_note         = \n| timezone1               = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +2\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +3\n| postal_code_type        = Postal code\n| postal_code             = \n| area_code               = \n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in Lebanon|Dialing code]]\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n| grid_position =184/283 [[Palestine grid|PAL]]\n| elevation_max_m         =\n\n}}\n\n'''Rachaf''' or '''Rchaf''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u0634\u0627\u0641}}) is a village in the [[Bint Jbeil District]] of the [[Nabatieh Governorate]] of [[Southern Lebanon]], 16 kilometres from the [[Israel]]-[[Lebanon]] border.\n\n== Etymology ==\nAccording to [[Edward Henry Palmer|Palmer]], the name means \"morass\" or \"bog.<ref>Palmer 1881, p. [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp00conduoft#page/97/mode/1up 97]</ref>\n== Location ==\nRachaf is situated 106&nbsp;km from Beirut, on a hill overlooking Srobbine and Debel villages. It covers an area of 608 hectares and is located 750m above sea level. The following villages border Rachaf : Srobbine - Debel - [[Al Tiri]] - [[Haddatha]] - Beit Leif. It can be reached by several routes, such as the following :\nSour - Aain Baal - Qana - Siddiqine - Kafra - [[Hariss]] - Haddatha - Rachaf\n==History==\nIn 1596, it was named as a village, ''ar-Rasaf'', in the [[Ottoman empire|Ottoman]] ''[[nahiya]]'' (subdistrict) of [[Tibnin]] under the ''[[Liwa (Arabic)|liwa']]'' (district) of [[Safad]], with a population of 51 households, all Muslim. The villagers paid a fixed tax rate of 25% on agricultural products, such as [[wheat]], [[barley]], fruit trees, goats and beehives, in addition to \"occasional revenues\"; a total of 2,720 [[ak\u00e7e]].<ref name=\"Hutteroth\">H\u00fctteroth and Abdulfattah, 1977, p. 180</ref><ref>Note that Rhode, 1979, p. [https://www.academia.edu/2026845/The_Administration_and_Population_of_the_Sancak_of_Safed_in_the_Sixteenth_Century 6] writes that the register that H\u00fctteroth and Abdulfattah studied was not from 1595/6, but from 1548/9</ref>\n\nIn 1881, the [[Palestine Exploration Fund|PEF]]'s [[PEF Survey of Palestine|''Survey of Western Palestine'' (SWP)]] described it: \"A stone village, containing about 100 [[Metawileh]], situated on a hill-top, with a few grapes, figs and olives, and arable cultivation; there is a spring near and cisterns in the village; also a birket for cattle.\u201d<ref>Conder and Kitchener, 1881, SWP I, p. [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp01conduoft#page/202/mode/1up 202]</ref>\n== Population ==\nThe registered population is estimated at 3,200 people. During the winter, the number of residents is approximately 300, a number which increases to 1,500 during summer. The low number of residents is because Rachaf was under Israeli occupation, which forced most of the residents to immigrate to the southern suburbs of [[Beirut]] and Sour, Aaitit, Al Rmadiyeh, Al Sarafand and Al Bazouriyeh. Despite the Israeli retreat in year 2000, migrants did not return to their village. However, the village has witnessed some renewed construction activities, with 200 additional houses built. There are 250 houses in the village distributed across 12 quarters: El Dayaa - Al Saha, Al Bayyad, Khalet El Maghara, Sahlet El Zaitoun, Al Rou\u00e9s, Al Dabsh Al Sharky, Al Dabsh Al Gharby, Al Assi, Al Maabour, Aain Jdeidah, Al Sowan, and Al Aaqaba.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Voters ==\nThe number of registered voters May 2004 was 1,690 (832 males and 858 females) compared to 1,505 voters in 2000, distributed mainly between 24 families.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Local Authorities ==\nThe village has a municipal council composed of 12 members. It was recently founded, based on the decision of the Minister of Interior and Municipalities no. 8 dated January 13, 2004. Rachaf has two mayors, one residing in the village and the other residing in Beirut southern suburb. The revenues that the municipality received from the independent municipal council in 2002 stood at LBP 115 million.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Educational and social institutions ==\nThe village has one primary public school with 26 registered students as of October 2004 - 9 in kindergarten and 17 in primary cycle. The school has 5 teachers. The total number of students in Rachaf is about 50, most of them registered in schools in Kafra and [[Bint Jbeil]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Economic Activities ==\nThe cultivated area constitutes only 5.6% of total land, while the arable land reaches 37% of the total area. The main products cultivated are olives, grains and tobacco. The Lebanese Reggie for Tobacco and Tombacs buys the entire tobacco production of the 22 farmers in the village. Oil, grains and other agricultural goods (tomatoes, cantaloupes, etc.) produced are sold in the village. Moreover, the production of honey is estimated at 500&nbsp;kg, which is sold inside the village at LBP 20,000-30,000/kilo.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n== Problems ==\nThe major problem in Rachaf is the emigration to other towns and cities. Furthermore, the village lacks a sewage system, which forces the residents to use cesspools. The poor health services due to the lack of dispensaries in the village forces the villagers to go to the dispensaries and hospitals located outside the village such as Tebnin Governmental Hospital (8&nbsp;km away) or Salah Ghandour Hospital (7&nbsp;km away).{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Conder|first1=C.R.|authorlink1=Claude Reignier Conder|last2=Kitchener|first2=H.H.|authorlink2=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|year=1881|url=https://archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp01conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Memoirs of the Topography, Orography, Hydrography, and Archaeology|location=London|publisher=[[Palestine Exploration Fund|Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund]]|volume=1}}\n*{{cite book | last1= H\u00fctteroth |first1=Wolf-Dieter |first2=Kamal | last2=Abdulfattah | title = Historical Geography of Palestine, Transjordan and Southern Syria in the Late 16th Century |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=wqULAAAAIAAJ | year = 1977 | publisher = Erlanger Geographische Arbeiten, Sonderband 5. Erlangen, Germany: Vorstand der Fr\u00e4nkischen Geographischen Gesellschaft|isbn= 3-920405-41-2}}\n*{{cite book|last=Palmer|first=E.H.|authorlink=Edward Henry Palmer|year=1881|url=https://archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp00conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Arabic and English Name Lists Collected During the Survey by Lieutenants Conder and Kitchener, R. E. Transliterated and Explained by E.H. Palmer|publisher=[[Palestine Exploration Fund|Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund]]}} \n*{{cite book|last=Rhode |first=H.|authorlink=Harold Rhode |date=1979 |url=https://www.academia.edu/2026845/The_Administration_and_Population_of_the_Sancak_of_Safed_in_the_Sixteenth_Century |title=Administration and Population of the Sancak of Safed in the Sixteenth Century |publisher=[[Columbia University]]}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*Survey of Western Palestine, Map 4: [http://www.iaa-archives.org.il/zoom/zoom.aspx?folder_id=93&type_id=6&id=8367 IAA], [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Survey_of_Western_Palestine_1880.04.jpg Wikimedia commons]\n*[http://www.localiban.org/article3474.html Rachaf], Localiban \n{{Bint Jbeil District}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Nabatieh Governorate]]\n[[Category:Bint Jbeil District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Rachaf\n| native_name             =  \u0631\u0634\u0627\u0641\n| native_name_lang        = ara<!-- ISO 639-2 code: \"fr\" for French, \"ara\" for Arabic -->\n| settlement_type         = Village\n\n| image_skyline           =\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           =\n\n| pushpin_map             = Lebanon\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = Map showing the location of Rachaf within Lebanon\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location within Lebanon\n\n| coordinates             = {{coord|33|09|N|35|22|E|region:LB_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{flagcountry|Lebanon}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Governorates of Lebanon|Governorate]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Districts of Lebanon|District]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Nabatieh Governorate]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Bint Jbeil District]]\n\n| established_title       = <!-- Founded -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 =\n\n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             =\n\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 700\n| elevation_min_m         = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n\n| population_note         = \n| timezone1               = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +2\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +3\n| postal_code_type        = Postal code\n| postal_code             = \n| area_code               = \n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in Lebanon|Dialing code]]\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n| grid_position =184/283 [[Palestine grid|PAL]]\n| elevation_max_m         =\n\n}}\n\n'''Rachaf''' or '''Rchaf'''  (\u0631\u0634\u0627\u0641) is a village in the [[Bint Jbeil District]] of the [[Nabatieh Governorate]] of [[Southern Lebanon]], 16 kilometres from the [[Israel]]-[[Lebanon]] border.\n\n== Etymology ==\nAccording to [[Edward Henry Palmer|Palmer]], the name means \"morass\" or \"bog.<ref>Palmer 1881, p. [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp00conduoft#page/97/mode/1up 97]</ref>\n== Location ==\nRachaf is situated 106&nbsp;km from Beirut, on a hill overlooking Srobbine and Debel villages. It covers an area of 608 hectares and is located 750m above sea level. The following villages border Rachaf : Srobbine - Debel - [[Al Tiri]] - [[Haddatha]] - Beit Leif. It can be reached by several routes, such as the following :\nSour - Aain Baal - Qana - Siddiqine - Kafra - [[Hariss]] - Haddatha - Rachaf\n==History==\nIn 1596, it was named as a village,  ''ar-Rasaf'', in the [[Ottoman empire|Ottoman]] ''[[nahiya]]'' (subdistrict) of  [[Tibnin]]  under the ''[[Liwa (Arabic)|liwa']]'' (district) of [[Safad]], with a population of  51  households, all Muslim. The villagers paid a fixed tax rate of 25 % on  agricultural products, such as [[wheat]], [[barley]], fruit trees, goats and beehives, in addition to \"occasional revenues\"; a total of 2,720 [[ak\u00e7e]].<ref name=\"Hutteroth\">H\u00fctteroth and Abdulfattah, 1977, p. 180</ref><ref>Note that Rhode, 1979, p. [https://www.academia.edu/2026845/The_Administration_and_Population_of_the_Sancak_of_Safed_in_the_Sixteenth_Century 6] writes that  the register that  H\u00fctteroth and  Abdulfattah  studied was not from 1595/6, but from 1548/9</ref>\n\nIn 1881, the [[Palestine Exploration Fund|PEF]]'s [[PEF Survey of Palestine|''Survey of Western Palestine'' (SWP)]]  described it: \"A stone village, containing about 100 [[Metawileh]], situated on a hill-top, with a few grapes, figs and olives, and arable cultivation; there is a spring near and cisterns in the village; also a birket for cattle.\u201d<ref>Conder and Kitchener, 1881, SWP I, p. [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp01conduoft#page/202/mode/1up 202]</ref>\n== Population ==\nThe registered population is estimated at 3,200 people. During the winter, the number of residents is approximately 300, a number which increases to 1,500 during summer. The low number of residents is because Rachaf was under Israeli occupation, which forced most of the residents to immigrate to the southern suburbs of [[Beirut]] and Sour, Aaitit, Al Rmadiyeh, Al Sarafand and Al Bazouriyeh. Despite the Israeli retreat in year 2000, migrants did not return to their village. However, the village has witnessed some renewed construction activities, with 200 additional houses built. There are 250 houses in the village distributed across 12 quarters: El Dayaa - Al Saha, Al Bayyad, Khalet El Maghara, Sahlet El Zaitoun, Al Rou\u00e9s, Al Dabsh Al Sharky, Al Dabsh Al Gharby, Al Assi, Al Maabour, Aain Jdeidah, Al Sowan, and Al Aaqaba.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Voters ==\nThe number of registered voters May 2004 was 1,690 (832 males and 858 females) compared to 1,505 voters in 2000, distributed mainly between 24 families.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Local Authorities ==\nThe village has a municipal council composed of 12 members. It was recently founded, based on the decision of the Minister of Interior and Municipalities no. 8 dated January 13, 2004. Rachaf has two mayors, one residing in the village and the other residing in Beirut southern suburb. The revenues that the municipality received from the independent municipal council in 2002 stood at LBP 115 million.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Educational and social institutions ==\nThe village has one primary public school with 26 registered students as of October 2004 - 9 in kindergarten and 17 in primary cycle. The school has 5 teachers. The total number of students in Rachaf is about 50, most of them registered in schools in Kafra and [[Bint Jbeil]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Economic Activities ==\nThe cultivated area constitutes only 5.6% of total land, while the arable land reaches 37% of the total area. The main products cultivated are olives, grains and tobacco. The Lebanese Reggie for Tobacco and Tombacs buys the entire tobacco production of the 22 farmers in the village. Oil, grains and other agricultural goods (tomatoes, cantaloupes, etc.) produced are sold in the village. Moreover, the production of honey is estimated at 500&nbsp;kg, which is sold inside the village at LBP 20,000-30,000/kilo.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n== Problems ==\nThe major problem in Rachaf is the emigration to other towns and cities. Furthermore, the village lacks a sewage system, which forces the residents to use cesspools. The poor health services due to the lack of dispensaries in the village forces the villagers to go to the dispensaries and hospitals located outside the village such as Tebnin Governmental Hospital (8&nbsp;km away) or Salah Ghandour Hospital (7&nbsp;km away).{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Conder|first1=C.R.|authorlink1=Claude Reignier Conder|last2=Kitchener|first2=H.H.|authorlink2=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|year=1881|url=https://archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp01conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Memoirs of the Topography, Orography, Hydrography, and Archaeology|location=London|publisher=[[Palestine Exploration Fund|Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund]]|volume=1}}\n*{{cite book | last1= H\u00fctteroth |first1=Wolf-Dieter |first2=Kamal | last2=Abdulfattah | title = Historical Geography of Palestine, Transjordan and Southern Syria in the Late 16th Century |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=wqULAAAAIAAJ  | year = 1977 | publisher = Erlanger Geographische Arbeiten, Sonderband 5. Erlangen, Germany: Vorstand der Fr\u00e4nkischen Geographischen Gesellschaft|isbn= 3-920405-41-2}}\n*{{cite book|last=Palmer|first=E.H.|authorlink=Edward Henry Palmer|year=1881|url=https://archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp00conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Arabic and English Name Lists Collected During the Survey by Lieutenants Conder and Kitchener, R. E. Transliterated and Explained by E.H. Palmer|publisher=[[Palestine Exploration Fund|Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund]]}} \n*{{cite book|last=Rhode |first=H.|authorlink=Harold Rhode |date=1979 |url=https://www.academia.edu/2026845/The_Administration_and_Population_of_the_Sancak_of_Safed_in_the_Sixteenth_Century   |title=Administration and Population of the Sancak of Safed in the Sixteenth Century   |publisher=[[Columbia University]]}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*Survey of Western Palestine, Map 4: [http://www.iaa-archives.org.il/zoom/zoom.aspx?folder_id=93&type_id=6&id=8367 IAA], [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Survey_of_Western_Palestine_1880.04.jpg Wikimedia commons]\n*[http://www.localiban.org/article3474.html  Rachaf], Localiban \n{{Bint Jbeil District}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Nabatieh Governorate]]\n[[Category:Bint Jbeil District]]\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rachaf"}
{"title_page": "Ella Mai", "text_new": "{{about|the singer|the eponymous album from the singer|Ella Mai (album)}}\n{{short description|British singer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ella Mai\n| image              = Ella_Mai_2019_by_Glenn_Francis.jpg\n| caption            = Mai at the [[2019 iHeartRadio Music Awards]]\n| birth_name         = Ella Mai Howell\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1994|11|3|df=25}}\n| birth_place        = [[London]], England\n| nationality        = British\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter}}\n| years_active       = 2014\u2013present\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed = Yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre = {{hlist|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Hip Hop music|hip hop]]|[[Pop music|pop]]}}\n| instrument = [[Vocals]]\n| label = {{hlist|10 Summers|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Mustard (record producer)|Mustard]]|[[H.E.R.]]|[[Chris Brown]]}}\n| website = {{URL|ellamai.com}}}}\n}}\n\n'''Ella Mai Howell''' (born 3 November 1994) is an British singer and songwriter. Her singing career began at the [[British and Irish Modern Music Institute]] in London in 2014, during which time she auditioned as part of a trio on the [[The X Factor (British series 11)|11th season]] of ''[[The X Factor (British TV series)|The X Factor]]''. In 2015, she uploaded a four-track solo EP of originals to SoundCloud titled Trouble, and was discovered on social media by American record producer [[Mustard (record producer)|Mustard]] and signed with his record label, 10 Summers Records.\n\nFrom 2016 to 2018, she released three [[Extended play|EP]]'s on the label, including ''Time'', ''Change'', and ''[[Ready (Ella Mai EP)|Ready]]''. Her [[Ella Mai (album)|self-titled debut studio album]] was released in October 2018 and featured the singles \"[[Boo'd Up]]\" and \"[[Trip (Ella Mai song)|Trip]]\", which were released on 20 February 2018 and 3 August 2018, respectively. In 2019, \"Boo'd Up\" was nominated for two [[Grammy Award]]s: [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Song|Best R&B Song]], winning for the latter, as well as Mai herself being nominated for [[Brit Award for British Breakthrough Act|British Breakthrough Act]] at the [[2019 Brit Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/idles-1975-dua-lipa-2019-brit-awards-nominations-2430434|title=IDLES, The 1975, and Dua Lipa amongst stars nominated for 2019 BRIT Awards|last=Daly|first=Rhian|date=12 January 2019|website=NME|accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> At the [[2019 Billboard Music Awards|2019 ''Billboard'' Music Awards]], she won three awards, including the award for [[Billboard Music Award for Top R&B Artist|Top R&B Artist]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Joe|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8509655/billboard-music-awards-2019-winners-list|title=2019 Billboard Music Awards Winners: The Complete List|website=Billboard|date=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nElla Mai was born on 3 November 1994 to a Jamaican mother and an Irish father<ref name=BillboardEllaMai>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8461270/ella-mai-chartbreaker-bood-up-interview|title=Chartbreaker: Ella Mai Can't Believe How Huge 'Boo'd Up' Has Become: 'I Have No Words'|website=Billboard.com|accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref> in [[London]]. According to the singer, her mother, a lover of American [[jazz]] music, named her after [[Ella Fitzgerald]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nylon.com/articles/ella-mai-interview|title=Ella Mai Makes The Music That We Can't Stop Listening To|date=24 March 2017|website=Nylon.com|accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref> Mai moved from London to [[New York City]] at the age of 12 and graduated from [[Queens High School of Teaching]] in [[Glen Oaks, Queens]], before returning to England.<ref name=BillboardEllaMai/>\n\n==Musical career==\n===2014\u20132017: Career beginnings and EP trilogy===\nElla Mai's singing career began studying at the [[British and Irish Modern Music Institute]] London (BIMM London) in 2014. During that time she competed on [[The X Factor (UK series 11)|season 11]] of ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'' as part of a trio, Arize, but didn't advance beyond the initial audition for the judges. The group broke up shortly thereafter. The following year, Mai uploaded a four-track solo EP of originals to [[SoundCloud]] titled ''Trouble''. After being discovered on [[Instagram]], she signed to [[DJ Mustard]]'s label, 10 Summers Records and [[Interscope Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.interscope.com/artists/ella-mai|title=Ella Mai|date=24 May 2018|website=Interscope.com}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, she released ''Time'', the first in her EP trilogy. The six-track EP included the single \"She Don't\", which featured [[Ty Dolla Sign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ella-mai-time-ep-new-mixtape.116276.html|title=Ella Mai \u2013 Time EP \u2013 Download & Listen [New Mixtape]|website=Hotnewhiphop.com}}</ref> She released her second EP, ''Change'', in November 2016 and third, ''[[Ready (Ella Mai EP)|Ready]]'', in February 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/2016/11/ella-mai-change-ep/|title=Take Ella Mai's New 'Change' EP For A Spin|date=22 November 2016|website=Vibe.com}}</ref> \"[[Boo'd Up]]\", which was featured on the EP, rose in popularity on social media as well as in nightclubs over the next few months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/05/24/ella-mai-bood-up-interview|title=Ella Mai's Slow Burn|last=Howard|first=Jackson|date=2018|website=The Fader|accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref> Ella Mai toured with [[Kehlani]] on her [[SweetSexySavage World Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://earmilk.com/2017/03/20/dj-mustard-signee-ella-mai-is-ready-to-be-a-household-name-in-rb-interview/|title=DJ Mustard signee Ella Mai is 'Ready' to be a household name in R&B [Interview] \u2013 EARMILK|date=20 March 2017|website=Earmilk.com}}</ref> After Mai served as the opening act on [[Kehlani]]'s tour, her music reached a bigger audience and the song grew on radio airplay in the spring of 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uproxx.com/hiphop/ella-mai-bood-up-billboard-hit-blew-up-r-b-comeback/|title=How Ella Mai's Unlikely 'Billboard' Hit 'Boo'd Up' Exploded In Popularity A Year After Its Release|last=Johnson|first=Cherise|date=15 June 2018|website=Uproxx|accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: Self-titled debut album===\nOn 26 April 2018, she released a music video for \"[[Boo'd Up]]\" after it started to gain popularity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8389217/ella-mai-bood-up-video|title=Ella Mai Premieres 'Boo'd Up' Video and Talks Debut Album: 'You Can Hear Growth'|last=|first=|date=|website=Billboard.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The song became her first top ten song in the US in the following month, deeming it her \"breakthrough hit.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8458488/ella-mai-bood-up-top-10-hot-100|title=Ella Mai Scores First Top 10 on Billboard Hot 100 With 'Boo'd Up'|last=Zellner|first=Xander|authorlink=|date=30 May 2018|website=Billboard|accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' wrote that the single is \"one of the biggest singles by a breakout female R&B singer in the past 10 years.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/ella-mais-bood-up-return-of-female-rb-singers-w520365|title='Boo'd Up': How Ella Mai Is Leading Female R&B Singers Back Onto the Charts|last=Leight|first=Elias|date=23 May 2018|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref> The single peaked at number five on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]],<ref name=\"Hot 100 peak\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8460299/post-malone-psycho-no-1-hot-100|title=Post Malone's 'Psycho' Hits No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100, Maroon 5's 'Girls Like You' Leaps to Top Five|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=11 June 2018|accessdate=12 June 2018}}</ref> and broke the record for the most weeks at No. 1 of any song by a woman on the [[R&B/Hip-Hop Airplay]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ella Mai's 'Boo'd Up' Sets Record For Most Weeks at No. 1 Among Women On R&B/Hip-Hop Airplay Chart |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8478283/ella-mai-bood-up-sets-record-rb-hip-hop-airplay-chart |website=Billboard}}</ref> On 14 August, she joined [[Bruno Mars]] on the [[24K Magic World Tour]] after [[Cardi B]] dropped out.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/news/bruno-mars-replaces-cardi-b-with-ciara-boyz-ii-men-and-more-on-24k-magic-tour/ar-BBLWJ9K|title=Bruno Mars Replaces Cardi B with Ciara, Boyz II Men and More on 24K Magic Tour|website=www.msn.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref> On 3 August, she released the single \"[[Trip (Ella Mai song)|Trip]]\", with an accompanied music video releasing on 18 September.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ella Mai Is Lovestruck on Her New Single 'Trip' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8468604/ella-mai-new-song-trip |website=Billboard}}</ref> The song peaked at number 11 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100. Ella Mai released her [[Ella Mai (album)|self-titled]] debut album, a 16-track set featuring \"Boo'd Up\", on 12 October 2018, with guest appearances from [[Chris Brown]], [[John Legend]], and [[H.E.R.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8479631/ella-mai-debut-album-stream-it-now|title=Ella Mai's Debut Album Is Here: Stream It Now|work=Billboard}}</ref> The album sold 69,000 [[album-equivalent units]] with 17,000 coming from pure sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8480932/a-star-is-born-soundtrack-second-week-no-1-billboard-200|title='A Star Is Born' Soundtrack Spends Second Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=21 October 2018}}</ref> On 22 October 2018, Mai announced her debut tour set to begin in January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8481003/ella-mai-tour-dates|title=Ella Mai Announces The Debut Tour: See the Dates|website=Billboard.com|accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2018/10/23/ella-mai-announces-her-2019-the-debut-tour/|title=Ella Mai Announces Her 2019 'The Debut Tour' - The Source|date=23 October 2018|website=Thesource.com|accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November, she made two guest appearances on [[JID]]'s song \"Tiiied\", along with [[6lack|6LACK]] and on [[Meek Mill]]'s song \"[[24/7 (Meek Mill song)|24/7]]\", on the albums [[DiCaprio 2|Dicapiro 2]] and [[Championships (album)|Championships]] respectively. On 18 November, she performed on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' with [[Jezebel (website)|''Jezebel'']] describing Mai as \"Pure '90s R&B Heartthrob\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/11/ella-mai-performs-trip-bood-up-on-snl-watch/|title=Ella Mai Performs \"Trip\" and \"Boo'd Up\" on 'SNL': Watch|date=18 November 2018|website=Spin.com|accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://jezebel.com/on-saturday-night-live-ella-mai-is-pure-90s-r-b-heartt-1830523774|title=On Saturday Night Live, Ella Mai is Pure '90s R&B Heartthrob|first=Emily|last=Alford|website=Jezebel.com|accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref> She was also nominated for two [[61st Grammy Awards|Grammy Awards]]: [[Best R&B Song]] and [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] with \"[[Boo'd Up]]\", winning for the former.<ref>{{cite web |title=ELLA MAI NOMINATED FOR GRAMMY AWARD |url=https://www.bimm.ie/news/ella-mai-nominated-for-grammy-award/ |website=BIMM |accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref> \"Boo'd Up\" would go onto to win the 2019 Billboard Music Award for Top R&B Song.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8509655/billboard-music-awards-2019-winners-list|title=2019 Billboard Music Awards Winners: The Complete List|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-05-02}}</ref> In 2019, Mai won the [[Billboard Music Award]]s for Top R&B Artist and Top Female R&B Artist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8509655/billboard-music-awards-2019-winners-list|title=2019 Billboard Music Awards Winners: The Complete List|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-05-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Mai received her third nomination for the [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Album]] for her self-titled debut at the [[62nd Grammy Awards]].\n\n==Artistry==\nIn multiple interviews, Ella Mai names [[Lauryn Hill]], [[Chris Brown]], [[Brandy Norwood|Brandy]], [[Destiny's Child]], [[Alicia Keys]], and [[Mariah Carey]] as her biggest influences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2017/10/01/chris-brown-previews-ella-mai-collaboration/|title=Chris Brown Previews Ella Mai Collaboration|website=Rap-up.com}}</ref> ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' said her \"perception of the powerful emotion is kindred to R&B heartthrobs of the \u201890s, who flooded the radio airwaves with soulful ballads, baby-making tunes, and heart-wrenching break-up anthems.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vibe.com/amp/2018/02/ella-mai-interview-next|title=NEXT: Ella Mai Is Bringing Confidence Back To R&#038;B Love Songs|date=26 February 2018|website=Vibe.com|first=Jessica|last=McKinney|accessdate=29 April 2019 }}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' described her sound as \"a British \u00e9migr\u00e9 full of self-confidence and an affinity for classic Nineties [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/10-new-artists-you-need-to-know-june-2017-w484147/ella-mai-w484212|title=10 New Artists You Need to Know Now|website=Rolling Stone}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of albums, with selected chart positions, sales, and certifications\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:9em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br /><ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/53595/ella-mai/|title=Ella Mai {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/albums-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Albums|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=22 October 2018|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br/>(FL)]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Ella+Mai|title=Discografie Ella Mai|publisher=[[Ultratop]]|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/ella-mai/chart-history/canadian-albums|title=Ella Mai \u2013 Chart History (Billboard Canadian Albums)|work=Billboard|accessdate=22 October 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Irish Albums Chart|IRE]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Albums|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=19 October 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[MegaCharts|NLD]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/s