{"title_page": "Massachusetts Route 32", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|type=Route\n|route=32\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Massachusetts Route 32}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Route 32 highlighted in red, Route 32A highlighted in blue\n|length_mi=60.686\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"MassDOT Route Log\"/>\n|length_round=3\n|formed=\n|direction_a=South\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=CT|CT|32}} in [[Monson, Massachusetts|Monson]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=MA|I|90|US|20}} in [[Palmer, Massachusetts|Palmer]]\n*{{jct|state=MA|MA|9}} in [[Ware, Massachusetts|Ware]]\n*{{jct|state=MA|MA|122}} in [[Barre, Massachusetts|Barre]]\n*{{jct|state=MA|US|202|MA|2}} in [[Athol, Massachusetts|Athol]]\n}}\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=NH|NH|32}} in [[Royalston, Massachusetts|Royalston]]\n|counties=[[Hampden County, Massachusetts|Hampden]], [[Hampshire County, Massachusetts|Hampshire]], [[Worcester County, Massachusetts|Worcester]]\n|previous_type=Route\n|previous_route=31\n|next_type=Route\n|next_route=33\n}}\n\n'''Massachusetts Route 32''' is a [[state highway]] in the U.S. state of [[Massachusetts]]. The highway runs {{convert|60.66|mi|km}} from the [[Connecticut]] state line in [[Monson, Massachusetts|Monson]], where the highway continues as [[Connecticut Route 32]], north to the [[New Hampshire]] state line in [[Royalston, Massachusetts|Royalston]], where the highway continues as [[New Hampshire Route 32]] (NH 32). Route 32 connects several towns on the eastern edge of [[Western Massachusetts]]. The highway serves [[Palmer, Massachusetts|Palmer]] in eastern [[Hampden County, Massachusetts|Hampden County]], [[Ware, Massachusetts|Ware]] in eastern [[Hampshire County, Massachusetts|Hampshire County]], and [[Barre, Massachusetts|Barre]] and [[Athol, Massachusetts|Athol]] in northwestern [[Worcester County, Massachusetts|Worcester County]]. Route 32 intersects major east&ndash;west routes including [[U.S. Route 20 in Massachusetts|U.S. Route 20]] (US 20) and the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]] in Palmer, [[Massachusetts Route 9|Route 9]] in Ware, and [[U.S. Route 202 in Massachusetts|US 202]] and [[Massachusetts Route 2|Route 2]] in Athol. The highway has an [[alternate route]], [[#Auxiliary route|Route 32A]], through [[Hardwick, Massachusetts|Hardwick]] and [[Petersham, Massachusetts|Petersham]].\n\n==Route description==\nRoute 32 begins at the Connecticut state line in the town of Monson in southeastern Hampden County, from which the highway continues south as Connecticut Route 32 toward [[Stafford Springs, Connecticut|Stafford Springs]]. The highway heads north as two-lane Stafford Road and immediately has an oblique grade crossing of the [[New England Central Railroad]]. Route 32 crosses the watershed divide between the Middle River and Chicopee Brook. The highway follows the rail line and intersects it south of South Monson, where the highway becomes named Main Street, and crosses over the railroad in Monson. Route 32 becomes Palmer Lower Road between the latter village and North Monson, where the highway crosses over the rail line and Chicopee Brook. The highway crosses the [[Quaboag River]], a tributary of the [[Chicopee River]], just east of the mouth of Chicopee Brook and enters the town of Palmer as Main Street. Route 32 turns north onto Stone Street, crosses over [[CSX Transportation|CSX]]'s [[Boston Subdivision]] rail line, and intersects US 20 (Park Street).\n\nRoute 32 [[concurrency (road)|runs concurrently]] west with US 20 along Park Street to downtown Palmer, where US 20 turns south onto Thorndike Street and Route 32 turns north. The highway intersects the connector from [[Interstate 90 in Massachusetts|Interstate 90]] (Massachusetts Turnpike) and heads northeast along Ware Street through Palmer Center to the town of Ware in Hampshire County. Shortly after entering the town, Route 32 passes under the [[Massachusetts Central Railroad]] and crosses the [[Ware River]]. The highway follows West Street to the center of town, where the highway intersects and joins Route 9 on Main Street. The highways cross the river, pass under the railroad, and leave town on East Street. The routes diverge just west of the Hampshire&ndash;Worcester county line, with Route 9 continuing east into [[West Brookfield, Massachusetts|West Brookfield]] and Route 32 turning north onto Gilbertville Road. The highway crosses back and forth between Ware and the Worcester County towns of West Brookfield and [[New Braintree, Massachusetts|New Braintree]] as it parallels the river and rail line north.\n\n[[File:New England Route 32 northbound entering Athol MA.jpg|thumb|left|Northbound Route 32 entering Athol]]\nRoute 32 enters Worcester County for good and enters the town of Hardwick just south of [[Gilbertville, Massachusetts|Gilbertville]], where the highway intersects the Massachusetts Central Railroad, crosses the Ware River, and meets the southern end of Route 32A (Hardwick Road). Route 32 exits the village on Church Street and continues northeast parallel to the rail line and river on Lower Road. The highway enters the town of Barre on Wheelwright Road. The route crosses the river and meets the northern end of [[Massachusetts Route 67|Route 67]] at its turn onto Main Street in the village of South Barre. Route 32 turns north again onto Barre Road and crosses the Ware River for the last time. The highway follows the Prince River to the town center of Barre, where the highway begins to run concurrently with [[Massachusetts Route 122|Route 122]] (Worcester Road) and meets the western end of [[Massachusetts Route 62|Route 62]] (Mechanic Street) at the Barre Common. Route 32 and Route 122 head west out of town on West Street, then veer north into Petersham, where they follow Barre Road. In the town center, Route 32 turns north onto Main Street while Route 122 continues on New Salem Road. The intersection serves as the northern terminus of Route 32A, which heads west concurrently with Route 122 then turns south on Hardwick Road west of the town center.\n\nRoute 32 meets the western end of [[Massachusetts Route 101|Route 101]] (Popple Camp Road) then has a [[partial cloverleaf]] interchange with [[U.S. Route 202 in Massachusetts|US 202]] and [[Massachusetts Route 2|Route 2]] shortly after entering the town of Athol on Petersham Road. The highway meets [[Massachusetts Route 2A|Route 2A]] (Templeton Road) north of the interchange; the highways head toward downtown along Main Street. Once there, Route 32 turns onto Chestnut Hill Avenue, crosses over the [[Pan Am Southern]] rail line and the [[Millers River]], then veers onto Silver Lake Street. The highway follows the East Branch of the Tully River into the town of Royalston as Athol-Richmond Road. Route 32 intersects [[Massachusetts Route 68|Route 68]] (Warwick Road) before reaching its northern terminus in the northwestern corners of both Royalston and Worcester County at the New Hampshire State line. The highway continues north into [[Richmond, New Hampshire|Richmond]] and toward [[Keene, New Hampshire|Keene]] along NH 32 (Athol Road).\n\n==History==\n{{Main article|New England Interstate Route 32}}\n[[Image:New England 32.svg|75px|right]]\nRoute 32 follows much of the course of the 1920s era New England Interstate Route 32, a part of the [[New England road marking system]] that ran from [[Groton, Connecticut]], through Palmer and Athol, to [[Newport, New Hampshire]].\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|length_ref=<ref name=\"MassDOT Route Log\">{{cite web|author=Planning Division|title=Massachusetts Highway Route Log|publisher=[[Massachusetts Department of Transportation]]|url=http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/planning/Main/MapsDataandReports/Maps/HighwayRouteLog.aspx|date=2009|accessdate=2014-01-05}}</ref>}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Hampden\n|cspan=4\n|location=Monson\n|mile=0.000\n|road={{jct|state=CT|CT|32|dir1=south|city1=Stafford Springs}}\n|notes=[[Connecticut]] state line\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Palmer\n|lspan=3\n|mile=8.791\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|20|dir1=east|name1=Park Street|city1=Brimfield|city2=Worcester}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of US 20 [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]]\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=9.846\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|20|dir1=west|name1=Thorndike Street|location1=[[Palmer, Massachusetts|Palmer Center]]|city2=Springfield}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of US 20 concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|type=etc\n|mile=10.439\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|90|MATP|location1=[[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester]]|city2=Boston|location3=[[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]]|location4=[[Albany, New York|Albany]]}}\n|notes=Exit 8 on I-90 / Massachusetts Turnpike\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Hampshire\n|cspan=2\n|location=Ware\n|lspan=2\n|mile=18.845\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|9|dir1=west|city1=Belchertown|city2=Amherst}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 9 concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=20.443\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|9|dir1=east|city1=Spencer|city2=Worcester}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 9 concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Worcester\n|cspan=11\n|location=Hardwick\n|mile=23.841\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|32A|dir1=north|name1=Hardwick Road|city1=Petersham}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 32A\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Barre\n|lspan=3\n|mile=31.386\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|67|dir1=south|name1=Main Street|city1=New Braintree|city2=North Brookfield}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 67\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=33.924\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|122|dir1=south|name1=Worcester Road|city1=Rutland|city2=Worcester}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 122 concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=35.060\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|62|dir1=east|name1=Mechanic Street|city1=Princeton|city2=Sterling}}\n|notes=Western terminus of Route 62\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Petersham\n|lspan=2\n|mile=42.415\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|122|MA|32A|to2=yes|dir1=north|dir2=south|name1=New Salem Road|city1=New Salem|city2=Orange}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 122 concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=43.877\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|101|dir1=north|name1=Popple Camp Road|city1=Templeton|city2=Gardner}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 101\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Athol\n|lspan=3\n|mile=48.830\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|202|MA|2|name2=Mohawk Trail|city1=Boston|city2=Winchendon|city3=Greenfield|city4=Belchertown}}\n|notes=Exit 17 on Route 2\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=49.718\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|2A|dir1=east|name1=Templeton Road|city1=Gardner}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 2A concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=51.080\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|2A|dir1=west|name1=Main Street|city1=Orange}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 2A concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Royalston\n|lspan=2\n|mile=58.577\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|68|dir1=south|name1=Warwick Road|city1=Baldwinville|city2=Gardner}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 68\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=60.686\n|road={{jct|state=NH|NH|32|dir1=north|city1=Keene}}\n|notes=[[New Hampshire]] state line\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur,etc}}\n\n==Auxiliary route==\n{{Infobox road small\n|state=MA\n|type=MA\n|route=32A\n|length_mi=12.791\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"MassDOT Route Log\"/>\n|location=[[Hardwick, Massachusetts|Hardwick]]&ndash;[[Petersham, Massachusetts|Petersham]]\n}}\n\n'''Massachusetts Route 32A''' is an [[alternate route]] of Route 32 in Hardwick and Petersham. The highway runs {{convert|12.791|mi|km}} between intersections with Route 32 in those towns, providing a more direct route that bypasses Barre. Route 32A begins in the Hardwick village of Gilbertville. The highway heads north through the town center of Hardwick and intersects Route 122 west of the center of Petersham. Route 32A runs concurrently east with Route 122 to its northern terminus at Route 32.\n\n<br>\n;Major intersections\n{{jcttop|state=MA|county=Worcester|length_ref=<ref name=googlemaps>{{google maps |url=https://goo.gl/maps/PGDCL9QdUBT6fZt37 |title=Route 32A |accessdate=June 2, 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Gilbertville\n|mile=0.0\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|32|nolink1=yes|city1=Barre|city2=Athol|city3=Ware}}\n|notes=Southern terminus\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Petersham\n|lspan=2\n|mile=12.3\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|122|dir1=north|city1=Orange}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 122 concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=12.8\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|32|MA|122|nolink1=yes|dir2=south|city1=Barre|City2=Worcester|city3=Petersham}}\n|notes=Northern terminus; northern terminus of Route 122 concurrency\n}}\n{{jctbtm}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Numbered routes in Massachusetts|032]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Hampden County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Hampshire County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Worcester County, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|type=Route\n|route=32\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Massachusetts Route 32}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Route 32 highlighted in red, Route 32A highlighted in blue\n|length_mi=60.686\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"MassDOT Route Log\"/>\n|length_round=3\n|formed=\n|direction_a=South\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=CT|CT|32}} in [[Monson, Massachusetts|Monson]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=MA|I|90|US|20}} in [[Palmer, Massachusetts|Palmer]]\n*{{jct|state=MA|MA|9}} in [[Ware, Massachusetts|Ware]]\n*{{jct|state=MA|MA|122}} in [[Barre, Massachusetts|Barre]]\n*{{jct|state=MA|US|202|MA|2}} in [[Athol, Massachusetts|Athol]]\n}}\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=NH|NH|32}} in [[Royalston, Massachusetts|Royalston]]\n|counties=[[Hampden County, Massachusetts|Hampden]], [[Hampshire County, Massachusetts|Hampshire]], [[Worcester County, Massachusetts|Worcester]]\n|previous_type=Route\n|previous_route=31\n|next_type=Route\n|next_route=33\n}}\n\n'''Massachusetts Route 32''' is a [[state highway]] in the U.S. state of [[Massachusetts]]. The highway runs {{convert|60.66|mi|km}} from the [[Connecticut]] state line in [[Monson, Massachusetts|Monson]], where the highway continues as [[Connecticut Route 32]], north to the [[New Hampshire]] state line in [[Royalston, Massachusetts|Royalston]], where the highway continues as [[New Hampshire Route 32]] (NH 32). Route 32 connects several towns on the eastern edge of [[Western Massachusetts]]. The highway serves [[Palmer, Massachusetts|Palmer]] in eastern [[Hampden County, Massachusetts|Hampden County]], [[Ware, Massachusetts|Ware]] in eastern [[Hampshire County, Massachusetts|Hampshire County]], and [[Barre, Massachusetts|Barre]] and [[Athol, Massachusetts|Athol]] in northwestern [[Worcester County, Massachusetts|Worcester County]]. Route 32 intersects major east&ndash;west routes including [[U.S. Route 20 in Massachusetts|U.S. Route 20]] (US 20) and the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]] in Palmer, [[Massachusetts Route 9|Route 9]] in Ware, and [[U.S. Route 202 in Massachusetts|US 202]] and [[Massachusetts Route 2|Route 2]] in Athol. The highway has an [[alternate route]], [[#Auxiliary route|Route 32A]], through [[Hardwick, Massachusetts|Hardwick]] and [[Petersham, Massachusetts|Petersham]].\n\n==Route description==\nRoute 32 begins at the Connecticut state line in the town of Monson in southeastern Hampden County, from which the highway continues south as Connecticut Route 32 toward [[Stafford Springs, Connecticut|Stafford Springs]]. The highway heads north as two-lane Stafford Road and immediately has an oblique grade crossing of the [[New England Central Railroad]]. Route 32 crosses the watershed divide between the Middle River and Chicopee Brook. The highway follows the rail line and intersects it south of South Monson, where the highway becomes named Main Street, and crosses over the railroad in Monson. Route 32 becomes Palmer Lower Road between the latter village and North Monson, where the highway crosses over the rail line and Chicopee Brook. The highway crosses the [[Quaboag River]], a tributary of the [[Chicopee River]], just east of the mouth of Chicopee Brook and enters the town of Palmer as Main Street. Route 32 turns north onto Stone Street, crosses over [[CSX Transportation|CSX]]'s [[Boston Subdivision]] rail line, and intersects US 20 (Park Street).\n\nRoute 32 [[concurrency (road)|runs concurrently]] west with US 20 along Park Street to downtown Palmer, where US 20 turns south onto Thorndike Street and Route 32 turns north. The highway intersects the connector from [[Interstate 90 in Massachusetts|Interstate 90]] (Massachusetts Turnpike) and heads northeast along Ware Street through Palmer Center to the town of Ware in Hampshire County. Shortly after entering the town, Route 32 passes under the [[Massachusetts Central Railroad]] and crosses the [[Ware River]]. The highway follows West Street to the center of town, where the highway intersects and joins Route 9 on Main Street. The highways cross the river, pass under the railroad, and leave town on East Street. The routes diverge just west of the Hampshire&ndash;Worcester county line, with Route 9 continuing east into [[West Brookfield, Massachusetts|West Brookfield]] and Route 32 turning north onto Gilbertville Road. The highway crosses back and forth between Ware and the Worcester County towns of West Brookfield and [[New Braintree, Massachusetts|New Braintree]] as it parallels the river and rail line north.\n\n[[File:New England Route 32 northbound entering Athol MA.jpg|thumb|left|Northbound Route 32 entering Athol]]\nRoute 32 enters Worcester County for good and enters the town of Hardwick just south of [[Gilbertville, Massachusetts|Gilbertville]], where the highway intersects the Massachusetts Central Railroad, crosses the Ware River, and meets the southern end of Route 32A (Hardwick Road). Route 32 exits the village on Church Street and continues northeast parallel to the rail line and river on Lower Road. The highway enters the town of Barre on Wheelwright Road. The route crosses the river and meets the northern end of [[Massachusetts Route 67|Route 67]] at its turn onto Main Street in the village of South Barre. Route 32 turns north again onto Barre Road and crosses the Ware River for the last time. The highway follows the Prince River to the town center of Barre, where the highway begins to run concurrently with [[Massachusetts Route 122|Route 122]] (Worcester Road) and meets the western end of [[Massachusetts Route 62|Route 62]] (Mechanic Street) at the Barre Common. Route 32 and Route 122 head west out of town on West Street, then veer north into Petersham, where they follow Barre Road. In the town center, Route 32 turns north onto Main Street while Route 122 continues on New Salem Road. The intersection serves as the northern terminus of Route 32A, which heads west concurrently with Route 122 then turns south on Hardwick Road west of the town center.\n\nRoute 32 meets the western end of [[Massachusetts Route 101|Route 101]] (Popple Camp Road) then has a [[partial cloverleaf]] interchange with [[U.S. Route 202 in Massachusetts|US 202]] and [[Massachusetts Route 2|Route 2]] shortly after entering the town of Athol on Petersham Road. The highway meets [[Massachusetts Route 2A|Route 2A]] (Templeton Road) north of the interchange; the highways head toward downtown along Main Street. Once there, Route 32 turns onto Chestnut Hill Avenue, crosses over the [[Pan Am Southern]] rail line and the [[Millers River]], then veers onto Silver Lake Street. The highway follows the East Branch of the Tully River into the town of Royalston as Athol-Richmond Road. Route 32 intersects [[Massachusetts Route 68|Route 68]] (Warwick Road) before reaching its northern terminus in the northwestern corners of both Royalston and Worcester County at the New Hampshire State line. The highway continues north into [[Richmond, New Hampshire|Richmond]] and toward [[Keene, New Hampshire|Keene]] along NH 32 (Athol Road).\n\n==History==\n{{Main article|New England Interstate Route 32}}\n[[Image:New England 32.svg|75px|right]]\nRoute 32 follows much of the course of the 1920s era New England Interstate Route 32, a part of the [[New England road marking system]] that ran from [[Groton, Connecticut]], through Palmer and Athol, to [[Newport, New Hampshire]].\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|length_ref=<ref name=\"MassDOT Route Log\">{{cite web|author=Planning Division|title=Massachusetts Highway Route Log|publisher=[[Massachusetts Department of Transportation]]|url=http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/planning/Main/MapsDataandReports/Maps/HighwayRouteLog.aspx|date=2009|accessdate=2014-01-05}}</ref>}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Hampden\n|cspan=4\n|location=Monson\n|mile=0.000\n|road={{jct|state=CT|CT|32|dir1=south|city1=Stafford Springs}}\n|notes=[[Connecticut]] state line\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Palmer\n|lspan=3\n|mile=8.791\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|20|dir1=east|name1=Park Street|city1=Brimfield|city2=Worcester}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of US 20 [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]]\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=9.846\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|20|dir1=west|name1=Thorndike Street|location1=[[Palmer, Massachusetts|Palmer Center]]|city2=Springfield}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of US 20 concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|type=etc\n|mile=10.439\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|90|MATP|city1=Boston|location2=[[Albany, New York|Albany, NY]]}}\n|notes=Exit 8 on I-90 / Massachusetts Turnpike\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Hampshire\n|cspan=2\n|location=Ware\n|lspan=2\n|mile=18.845\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|9|dir1=west|city1=Belchertown|city2=Amherst}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 9 concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=20.443\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|9|dir1=east|city1=Spencer|city2=Worcester}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 9 concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Worcester\n|cspan=11\n|location=Hardwick\n|mile=23.841\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|32A|dir1=north|name1=Hardwick Road|city1=Petersham}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 32A\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Barre\n|lspan=3\n|mile=31.386\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|67|dir1=south|name1=Main Street|city1=New Braintree|city2=North Brookfield}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 67\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=33.924\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|122|dir1=south|name1=Worcester Road|city1=Rutland|city2=Worcester}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 122 concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=35.060\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|62|dir1=east|name1=Mechanic Street|city1=Princeton|city2=Sterling}}\n|notes=Western terminus of Route 62\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Petersham\n|lspan=2\n|mile=42.415\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|122|MA|32A|to2=yes|dir1=north|dir2=south|name1=New Salem Road|city1=New Salem|city2=Orange}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 122 concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=43.877\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|101|dir1=north|name1=Popple Camp Road|city1=Templeton|city2=Gardner}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 101\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Athol\n|lspan=3\n|mile=48.830\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|202|MA|2|name2=Mohawk Trail|city1=Boston|city2=Winchendon|city3=Greenfield|city4=Belchertown}}\n|notes=Exit 17 on Route 2\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=49.718\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|2A|dir1=east|name1=Templeton Road|city1=Gardner}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 2A concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=51.080\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|2A|dir1=west|name1=Main Street|city1=Orange}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 2A concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Royalston\n|lspan=2\n|mile=58.577\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|68|dir1=south|name1=Warwick Road|city1=Baldwinville|city2=Gardner}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 68\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=60.686\n|road={{jct|state=NH|NH|32|dir1=north|city1=Keene}}\n|notes=[[New Hampshire]] state line\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur,etc}}\n\n==Auxiliary route==\n{{Infobox road small\n|state=MA\n|type=MA\n|route=32A\n|length_mi=12.791\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"MassDOT Route Log\"/>\n|location=[[Hardwick, Massachusetts|Hardwick]]&ndash;[[Petersham, Massachusetts|Petersham]]\n}}\n\n'''Massachusetts Route 32A''' is an [[alternate route]] of Route 32 in Hardwick and Petersham. The highway runs {{convert|12.791|mi|km}} between intersections with Route 32 in those towns, providing a more direct route that bypasses Barre. Route 32A begins in the Hardwick village of Gilbertville. The highway heads north through the town center of Hardwick and intersects Route 122 west of the center of Petersham. Route 32A runs concurrently east with Route 122 to its northern terminus at Route 32.\n\n<br>\n;Major intersections\n{{jcttop|state=MA|county=Worcester|length_ref=<ref name=googlemaps>{{google maps |url=https://goo.gl/maps/PGDCL9QdUBT6fZt37 |title=Route 32A |accessdate=June 2, 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Gilbertville\n|mile=0.0\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|32|nolink1=yes|city1=Barre|city2=Athol|city3=Ware}}\n|notes=Southern terminus\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Petersham\n|lspan=2\n|mile=12.3\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|122|dir1=north|city1=Orange}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 122 concurrency\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=12.8\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|32|MA|122|nolink1=yes|dir2=south|city1=Barre|City2=Worcester|city3=Petersham}}\n|notes=Northern terminus; northern terminus of Route 122 concurrency\n}}\n{{jctbtm}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Numbered routes in Massachusetts|032]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Hampden County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Hampshire County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Worcester County, Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "2601:192:103:3000:15fc:b4a4:b3b8:741b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massachusetts_Route_32"}
{"title_page": "Massachusetts Route 21", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|type=Route\n|route=21\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=320|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Massachusetts Route 21}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Route 21 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=13.73\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"massdot route log\">{{cite web|author=Planning Division|title=Massachusetts Highway Route Log|publisher=[[Massachusetts Department of Transportation]]|url=http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/planning/Main/MapsDataandReports/Maps/HighwayRouteLog.aspx|date=2012|accessdate=March 8, 2015}}</ref>\n|established=\n|direction_a=South\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=MA|US|20|MA|141}} in [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=MA|I|90}} in [[Ludlow, Massachusetts|Ludlow]]\n*{{jct|state=MA|US|202|MA|181}} in [[Belchertown, Massachusetts|Belchertown]]}}\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=MA|MA|9}} in Belchertown\n|counties=[[Hampden County, Massachusetts|Hampden]], [[Hampshire County, Massachusetts|Hampshire]]\n|previous_type=Route\n|previous_route=20A\n|next_type=Route\n|next_route=22\n|}}\n\n'''Route 21''' is a {{convert|13.73|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} south\u2013north [[state highway]] in [[Massachusetts]] that runs between [[U.S. Route 20 in Massachusetts|U.S. Route 20]] (US 20) and [[Massachusetts Route 141|Route 141]] in [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]] and [[Massachusetts Route 9|Route 9]] in [[Belchertown, Massachusetts|Belchertown]]. Along the way it intersects several major highways including [[Massachusetts Turnpike|Interstate 90]] (I-90) in [[Ludlow, Massachusetts|Ludlow]] and [[U.S. Route 202 in Massachusetts|US 202]] and [[Massachusetts Route 181|Route 181]] in [[Belchertown, Massachusetts|Belchertown]].\n\n==Route description==\n[[Image:MA Route 21 northbound entering Ludlow, MA.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Route 21 northbound entering Ludlow]]\nThe route begins at [[U.S. Route 20]] in the Indian Orchard section of Springfield.  It heads north, intersecting with [[Massachusetts Route 141|Route 141]] before crossing the [[Chicopee River]] into [[Ludlow, Massachusetts|Ludlow]].  Once in Ludlow, the road continues in a northeasterly direction.  It passes under the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]], with access to that road via Exit 7.  It continues through town, passing south of the Springfield Reservoir before heading northward into Belchertown.  In Belchertown it shares a concurrency with [[U.S. Route 202]], which ends at [[Massachusetts Route 181|Route 181]].  From there Route 21 makes its final short trek to its current terminus at [[Massachusetts Route 9|Route 9]].\n\n==History== \nPrior to the completion of the [[Quabbin Reservoir]], Route 21 extended further northward.  It passed through the former town of [[Enfield, Massachusetts|Enfield]], then northward along the Swift River into [[Greenwich, Massachusetts|Greenwich]] and the northern end of [[Dana, Massachusetts|Dana]] before heading through the current town of [[Petersham, Massachusetts|Petersham]] and into [[Athol, Massachusetts|Athol]], where it terminated at what is now [[Massachusetts Route 2A|Route 2A]].  The southern portion of the road (Old Enfield Road) is still accessible in Belchertown. The northern trunk follows Pleasant Street and New Sherborn Road in Athol, then the Monson Turnpike (Turnpike Road) in Petersham, where the road had an intersection with [[Massachusetts Route 122|Route 122]].  Much of the route south of this intersection lies within the Quabbin Reservoir State Reservation.<ref>Tougias, Michael. ''Quabbin: A History and Explorers Guide''. Yarmouth Port, Massachusetts: On Cape Publications, 2002, p.48.</ref>\n\nInto the 1970s. MA-21 Started in Forest Park with an Intersection with [[U.S. Route 5]] near the South End Bridge, today [[Interstate 91]] now overtakes that intersection along with [[Massachusetts Route 83|MA-83]]. From there, the route went down Longhill Street until Sumner Avenue. Through the 6 way Intersection with Belmont Avenue and Dickinson Street, known to locals as the X. From there, the route went down Sumner until the intersection with Allen Street which then made a turn onto Cooley Street at the Sixteen Acres section of town. From there, Cooley Street continued north into Parker Street which took drivers to today's terminus, outside of Indian Orchard. There were plans to bypass this with the Springfield Bypass but it was never completed. Only a small part where Summner and Allen Streets were made for the highway and a short highway bypass of Allen and Cooley Streets known as Bicentennial Highway was constructed to relieve passengers. It is unknown why it was shortened, speculation includes to ease the traffic through that section and to keep motorists away since that area of town was some of the most dangerous in the 1970s. Today, MA-83 overtook the route from the X down to Route 5 and Interstate 91.\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|state=MA|length_ref=<ref name=\"massdot route log\"/>}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Hampden\n|cspan=3\n|location=Springfield\n|lspan=2\n|mile=0.00\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|20|MA|141|city1=Palmer|city2=Worcester|city3=Westfield|city4=Pittsfield}}\n|notes=Southern terminus; eastern terminus of Route 141 and [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]] with Route 21\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=1.19\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|141|dir1=west|city1=Chicopee Falls|city2=Holyoke}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of concurrency with Route&nbsp;141\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Ludlow\n|mile=2.32\n|type=etc|road={{jct|state=MA|I|90|MATP|location1=[[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester]]|city2=Boston|location3=[[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]]|location4=[[Albany, New York|Albany]]}}\n|notes= Exit&nbsp;54 on I-90 / Mass Pike (formerly exit 7)\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Hampshire\n|cspan=3\n|location=Belchertown\n|lspan=3\n|mile=11.94\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|202|dir1=south|city1=Granby|city2=Holyoke}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of concurrency with US&nbsp;202\n}}\n{{MAint\n|type=concur\n|mile=12.94\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|202|MA|181|dir1=north|dir2=south|city1=Pelham|city2=Bondsville|city3=Palmer}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of concurrency with US&nbsp;202; northern terminus of Route&nbsp;181\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=13.73\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|9|city1=Amherst|city2=Northampton|city3=Ware|city4=Worcester}}\n|notes=Northern terminus\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur,etc}}\n\n==References==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{Commons category|Massachusetts Route 21}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Numbered routes in Massachusetts|021]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|type=Route\n|route=21\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=320|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Massachusetts Route 21}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Route 21 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=13.73\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"massdot route log\">{{cite web|author=Planning Division|title=Massachusetts Highway Route Log|publisher=[[Massachusetts Department of Transportation]]|url=http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/planning/Main/MapsDataandReports/Maps/HighwayRouteLog.aspx|date=2012|accessdate=March 8, 2015}}</ref>\n|established=\n|direction_a=South\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=MA|US|20|MA|141}} in [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=MA|I|90}} in [[Ludlow, Massachusetts|Ludlow]]\n*{{jct|state=MA|US|202|MA|181}} in [[Belchertown, Massachusetts|Belchertown]]}}\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=MA|MA|9}} in Belchertown\n|counties=[[Hampden County, Massachusetts|Hampden]], [[Hampshire County, Massachusetts|Hampshire]]\n|previous_type=Route\n|previous_route=20A\n|next_type=Route\n|next_route=22\n|}}\n\n'''Route 21''' is a {{convert|13.73|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} south\u2013north [[state highway]] in [[Massachusetts]] that runs between [[U.S. Route 20 in Massachusetts|U.S. Route 20]] (US 20) and [[Massachusetts Route 141|Route 141]] in [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]] and [[Massachusetts Route 9|Route 9]] in [[Belchertown, Massachusetts|Belchertown]]. Along the way it intersects several major highways including [[Massachusetts Turnpike|Interstate 90]] (I-90) in [[Ludlow, Massachusetts|Ludlow]] and [[U.S. Route 202 in Massachusetts|US 202]] and [[Massachusetts Route 181|Route 181]] in [[Belchertown, Massachusetts|Belchertown]].\n\n==Route description==\n[[Image:MA Route 21 northbound entering Ludlow, MA.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Route 21 northbound entering Ludlow]]\nThe route begins at [[U.S. Route 20]] in the Indian Orchard section of Springfield.  It heads north, intersecting with [[Massachusetts Route 141|Route 141]] before crossing the [[Chicopee River]] into [[Ludlow, Massachusetts|Ludlow]].  Once in Ludlow, the road continues in a northeasterly direction.  It passes under the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]], with access to that road via Exit 7.  It continues through town, passing south of the Springfield Reservoir before heading northward into Belchertown.  In Belchertown it shares a concurrency with [[U.S. Route 202]], which ends at [[Massachusetts Route 181|Route 181]].  From there Route 21 makes its final short trek to its current terminus at [[Massachusetts Route 9|Route 9]].\n\n==History== \nPrior to the completion of the [[Quabbin Reservoir]], Route 21 extended further northward.  It passed through the former town of [[Enfield, Massachusetts|Enfield]], then northward along the Swift River into [[Greenwich, Massachusetts|Greenwich]] and the northern end of [[Dana, Massachusetts|Dana]] before heading through the current town of [[Petersham, Massachusetts|Petersham]] and into [[Athol, Massachusetts|Athol]], where it terminated at what is now [[Massachusetts Route 2A|Route 2A]].  The southern portion of the road (Old Enfield Road) is still accessible in Belchertown. The northern trunk follows Pleasant Street and New Sherborn Road in Athol, then the Monson Turnpike (Turnpike Road) in Petersham, where the road had an intersection with [[Massachusetts Route 122|Route 122]].  Much of the route south of this intersection lies within the Quabbin Reservoir State Reservation.<ref>Tougias, Michael. ''Quabbin: A History and Explorers Guide''. Yarmouth Port, Massachusetts: On Cape Publications, 2002, p.48.</ref>\n\nInto the 1970s. MA-21 Started in Forest Park with an Intersection with [[U.S. Route 5]] near the South End Bridge, today [[Interstate 91]] now overtakes that intersection along with [[Massachusetts Route 83|MA-83]]. From there, the route went down Longhill Street until Sumner Avenue. Through the 6 way Intersection with Belmont Avenue and Dickinson Street, known to locals as the X. From there, the route went down Sumner until the intersection with Allen Street which then made a turn onto Cooley Street at the Sixteen Acres section of town. From there, Cooley Street continued north into Parker Street which took drivers to today's terminus, outside of Indian Orchard. There were plans to bypass this with the Springfield Bypass but it was never completed. Only a small part where Summner and Allen Streets were made for the highway and a short highway bypass of Allen and Cooley Streets known as Bicentennial Highway was constructed to relieve passengers. It is unknown why it was shortened, speculation includes to ease the traffic through that section and to keep motorists away since that area of town was some of the most dangerous in the 1970s. Today, MA-83 overtook the route from the X down to Route 5 and Interstate 91.\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|state=MA|length_ref=<ref name=\"massdot route log\"/>}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Hampden\n|cspan=3\n|location=Springfield\n|lspan=2\n|mile=0.00\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|20|MA|141|city1=Palmer|city2=Worcester|city3=Westfield|city4=Pittsfield}}\n|notes=Southern terminus; eastern terminus of Route 141 and [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]] with Route 21\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=1.19\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|141|dir1=west|city1=Chicopee Falls|city2=Holyoke}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of concurrency with Route&nbsp;141\n}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Ludlow\n|mile=2.32\n|type=etc\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|90|MATP||city1=Boston|location2=[[Albany, New York|Albany, NY]]}}\n|notes= Exit&nbsp;54 on I-90 / Mass Pike (formerly exit 7)\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Hampshire\n|cspan=3\n|location=Belchertown\n|lspan=3\n|mile=11.94\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|202|dir1=south|city1=Granby|city2=Holyoke}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of concurrency with US&nbsp;202\n}}\n{{MAint\n|type=concur\n|mile=12.94\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|202|MA|181|dir1=north|dir2=south|city1=Pelham|city2=Bondsville|city3=Palmer}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of concurrency with US&nbsp;202; northern terminus of Route&nbsp;181\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=13.73\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|9|city1=Amherst|city2=Northampton|city3=Ware|city4=Worcester}}\n|notes=Northern terminus\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur,etc}}\n\n==References==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{Commons category|Massachusetts Route 21}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Numbered routes in Massachusetts|021]]\n", "name_user": "2601:192:103:3000:15fc:b4a4:b3b8:741b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massachusetts_Route_21"}
{"title_page": "Massachusetts Route 33", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|type=MA\n|route=33\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Massachusetts Route 33}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Route 33 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=5.54\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"inventory\">[[Executive Office of Transportation (Massachusetts)|Executive Office of Transportation]], [http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content/plan02&sid=about Office of Transportation Planning - 2007 Road Inventory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927193052/http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content%2Fplan02&sid=about |date=2006-09-27 }}</ref>\n|length_round=2\n|established={{circa}} 1946\n|direction_a=South\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=MA|MA|141}} in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee]]\n|junction={{jct|state=MA|I|90}} in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee]]<br />{{jct|state=MA|US|202}} in [[South Hadley, Massachusetts|South Hadley]]\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=MA|MA|116}} in [[South Hadley, Massachusetts|South Hadley]]\n|counties=[[Hampden County, Massachusetts|Hampden]], [[Hampshire County, Massachusetts|Hampshire]]\n|previous_type=MA\n|previous_route=32A\n|next_type=MA\n|next_route=35\n}}\n\n'''Route 33''' is a {{convert|5.54|mi|km|-long|adj=mid}} [[state highway]] contained entirely within the city of [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee]] and the town of [[South Hadley, Massachusetts|South Hadley]] in [[Massachusetts]]. Its southern terminus is at [[Massachusetts Route 141|Route 141]] and its northern terminus is at [[Massachusetts Route 116|Route 116]].\n\n==Route description==\nRoute 33 begins at [[Massachusetts Route 141|Route 141]] just north of the [[Chicopee River]] in the Chicopee Falls section of the city.  It crosses under the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]], with the entrance ramps for Exit 5 just north of this.  It passes west of [[Westover Joint Air Reserve Base]] before entering the town of South Hadley.  Once in South Hadley, the road crosses [[U.S. Route 202]], which leads westward towards [[Holyoke, Massachusetts|Holyoke]], as it turns northeast, ending at [[Massachusetts Route 116|Route 116]], the street itself continuing as Lyman Street.\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Hampden\n|cspan=2\n|location=Chicopee\n|lspan=2\n|mile=0.0\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|141|location1=[[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee Center]]|city2=Indian Orchard|city3=Ludlow|city4=Holyoke}}\n|notes=Southern terminus\n}}\n{{MAint\n|type=etc\n|mile=0.9\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|90|MATP|location1=[[Worcester]]|location2=[[Boston]]|location3=[[Albany, NY]]}}\n|notes=Exit 5 on I-90 / Massachusetts Turnpike\n}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Hampshire\n|cspan=2\n|location=South Hadley\n|lspan=2\n|mile=4.6\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|202|city1=Granby|city2=Belchertown|city3=Holyoke}}\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=5.54\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|116|MA|47|to2=yes|city1=Amherst|city2=Greenfield|city3=Holyoke}}\n|notes=Northern terminus\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=etc}}\n\n==References==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Numbered routes in Massachusetts|033]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Hampden County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Hampshire County, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|type=MA\n|route=33\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Massachusetts Route 33}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Route 33 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=5.54\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"inventory\">[[Executive Office of Transportation (Massachusetts)|Executive Office of Transportation]], [http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content/plan02&sid=about Office of Transportation Planning - 2007 Road Inventory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927193052/http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp